\b\fs24 Features\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 A game timer is shown above the turn timer. (In replays, it has full precision; in game play, it has hours and minutes.) This is useful for referencing moments in replays, and is also a stopgap until bookmarking and cropping are implemented.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The turn timer no longer "fades in" during replays, so that the duration of a very short turn can be read easily.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Precise fuse timers are shown during replays.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The phone icon is now displayed in whichever corner is least intrusive.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The display can now be scrolled while paused in Single Step mode during a replay.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Features affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 Worms can now change direction and fire a weapon in the same instant. (This is similar to a change in v3.5 Beta 1, which allowed one to change direction and jump in the same instant.) So for example, in a Battle Race, you can now land from a jump, hold the key to face in the opposite direction and fire the shotgun immediately after landing without worrying that your worm may fire in the wrong direction if your timing is perfect.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Utilities can now be toggled; for example, if you use Low Gravity after it has been activated, it is cancelled.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Worms can now walk backwards. When you hold the Shift key and walk, your Worm will not change the direction in which it is facing. This is useful for fine-tuning your position prior to a jump or shotgun shot, for example.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 Switched to Visual C++ 7 for compiling, with Whole Program Optimization. This may make the game engine a bit faster (e.g. for faster, smoother fast-forwards in replays).\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
\cf4\b v3.6.20.2 Beta Update (2004.08.03)\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.20.1: Some people experienced a jerky game, for a reason entirely unrelated to that which the timer workaround addressed. It was caused by the v3.6.20.1 fix \i "W:A no longer uses 100% CPU unnecessarily."\i0  and is now resolved; it turns out that in-game, 100% CPU usage only ever occurred while minimised; yet in v3.6.20.1, the fix was applied even when the game was in the foreground.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.20.1: To avoid distraction, the phone icon (which could swap sides at any time in v3.6.20.1) now only swaps sides while hidden.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Fixes affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 Bug introduced in v3.6.20.1: Instant replays could diverge from what actually happened, especially if roping or mines were involved. Through a loophole, this also allowed the offline use of slow motion. The possible earlier use of the loophole is now reported when playing back replays in which it was used (pull down the chat to see such messages).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}In v3.6.20.1, schemes that had been externally edited to give weapons power levels higher than 5 stars no longer worked in the same way as they had in earlier versions. This caused desyncs when playing back replays and playing online games using such schemes. Now, compatibility is restored, as long as the power levels lie within some "standard" ranges. All weapons must be <=20 stars; Mortar, Cluster Bomb, Banana Bomb, Air Strike and Napalm Strike must be <=15 stars; Skunk and Longbow must be <=10 stars; Axe must be <=5 stars. Schemes that break these limits will bring up a warning when loaded or when a replay is opened.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Worms can now \i always\i0  dismount the Jet Pack or Parachute by pressing Space, whereas before, this was not possible in Artillery mode (in which worms are forbidden from walking or jumping).\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
\cf4\b v3.6.20.3 Beta Update (2004.08.06)\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 There was a bug in v3.6.20.2 causing improper emulation of v3.6.20.1. Using clustered weapons, skunks, longbows or axes could cause a desync. Now, v3.6.20.1 is properly emulated.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}To avoid invoking v3.6.20.2's improper emulation of v3.6.20.1, this version 3.6.20.3, when hosting, will avoid emulating .20.1 if there are players with .20.2 present; in this case it will emulate 3.6.19.19 instead. Note that there is still an exception in which a desync can happen: if you are not the host of a game, and the other people in it have a mixture of .20.1 and .20.2, then during the game the .20.2 players may desync and drop out. If the host is running .20.2 then the whole game could desync.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The instant replay fix in v3.6.20.2 was incomplete, and could cause a crash.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
\cf4\b v3.6.21.1 Beta Update (2004.09.23)\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 One of the ways in which W:A didn't work under Windows 2000/XP before v3.5 Beta 1, was that it would hang when switching from the front end to gameplay mode, right before the piechart would have been shown. It was possible to fool it into starting anyway (by Alt-Tabbing to one of the W:A processes, or in some cases something more complex), but the palette would be wrong and the update rate would be slow. As it turns out, the fix was not complete, because this bug would sometimes still happen. Now there is a more correct fix that goes closer to the root of this problem, and it may solve problems some people have been having trying to start a game.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Even when instant replays were disabled in the scheme, one would still be shown after a Worm had skimmed water or used a Kamikaze, despite the v3.6.19.17 fix.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}When using the mouse to point a Strike weapon, the cursor was initially pointed 45\'b0 left/right from down. If the angle was adjusted with the Left/Right arrows, it would still point 45\'b0 right but would point 34\'b0 left. This is now fixed. On the other hand, the cursor for Teleport and other targeted weapons was originally intended to point 45\'b0 up-left, but everybody is used to that fact that it points 34\'b0 left from up. This is caused by a glitch, but a change would be disorienting, so the 34\'b0 angle has been preserved.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Ran Profiling on W:A to find where the CPU spends most of its time in-game, with some interesting and helpful results.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 The function to render flaming health bars was always being executed, whether or not any flaming bars were actually being displayed. This routine was unoptimised and very processor intensive. It is now much more efficient, and furthermore will not run unless needed.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Fixed-point multiplication has now been inlined, creating a global speed-up. (Sea bubbles were a heavy user of multiplication, so there's a speed-up even in idle conditions.)\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}These changes allow for better performance when fast-forwarding replays, and should also help to keep the frame rate steady during normal play.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 In games recorded with v3.6.19.15 or later, chat messages that were made after a pending game-over were not being shown during playback.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Fixes affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 The Girder Radius (maximum ortho-distance between your worm and any possible place you can place a girder) is now calculated from the centre of the girder. Previously, it was calculated from the upper-left corner of an orthogonal rectangle encompassing the girder, which was asymmetric and non-intuitive. Note that the radius actually defines a diamond rather than a circle, as with many things in W:A; ortho-distance is the sum of horizontal and vertical distance, as opposed to distance which is the square root of the sum of the squares of horizontal and vertical distances.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}If an animal (such as a sheep) was sent out to collect a health crate, and the Worm sending it died before collection, the health would still be added to its team total. This could cause the game to see that team as "alive" even after all its worms died out; but when the turn passed to that team, the game would crash. Now, health crates will not be collected by an animal sent by a now-dead Worm. \b (See Footnote 2.)\b0\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}After using Rope, Bungee or Parachute, a player would always get Air retreat time on that turn, even if using a weapon from the ground.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}It was possible to fire a ground-only weapon in the single frame (1/50 second) step between walking off a ledge and falling. The weapon would not fire, but would incur retreat time. Now, such an attempt will result in a warning beep.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Under certain very rare circumstances, a roping Worm could become stuck against a wall at the same moment the rope unsnagged, causing it to be trapped in that spot until dismounting from the rope. This also caused the game's CPU usage to soar until the rope was dismounted.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The parachute/fall damage speed threshold mismatch was indeed fixed once and for all in v3.6.20.1. However, there was again a small area between vertical speed thresholds where a Worm that fell out of a roll or slide would twang without accruing fall damage, as there was in v3.6.19.7.\cf1  [This was finally a complete fix.]\cf0\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Normal mines were not triggered by a Frozen Worm, but mines from a Mine Strike were.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Under certain rare circumstances, a dud mine could explode. The condition for this made no sense; it didn't have anything to do with blasting or knocking the mine, but rather happened when the centre of the mine was within 1 pixel of the centre of a worm at the right moment. This is now disabled and may in a future version be replaced with something more sensible.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
\b\fs24 Changes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 Some people experience a palette bug in which background apps can steal the palette from W:A, corrupting some or all of its colours. W:A will now log these to "palette.log" located in your main Worms Armageddon folder. Note that the problem can still happen; the only change is that it is logged. This information gleaned from this may lead to finding a fix.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
\b\fs24 Features\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 It is now possible to play replays as fast as your machine is likely to handle, and at 1.5\'d7 as well. The [1]-[9] keys now correspond to 1\'d7,1.5\'d7,2\'d7,3\'d7,4\'d7,6\'d7,8\'d7,12\'d7,16\'d7. Hold [0] while pressing [1]-[9] and you will get 24\'d7,32\'d7,48\'d7,64\'d7,96\'d7,128\'d7,192\'d7,256\'d7,384\'d7. (As before, holding Shift while pressing [1]-[9] will set slow-motion; the multiplier chart becomes a divider chart.)\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The frame rate will not be allowed to drop significantly below 10 fps. Thus the keyboard will no longer become very unresponsive during a fast-forward which taxes the CPU.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}As before, holding the left mouse button during a replay will override automatic camera motion. This now works in an online game during other players' turns. In addition, turning on CAPS LOCK will override the camera during a replay.\cf1  [Caps Lock no longer has this function. See the entry for v3.6.26.4.]\cf0\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}There is now a Log Extraction feature which can be applied on game recordings. Right-click on a \b .WAgame\b0  file and choose "\b Extract Log\b0 ", and the game information, chat and major game events (with timestamps in game time) and end-game stats will be logged to a file in the same folder with the same base filename.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Features affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 In Cavern levels, the Teleport and homing/strike weapons can now be pointed within a slightly larger range, encompassing the leftmost and rightmost positions where a Worm may stand on the edges of the landscape. While pointing near the rightmost edge, the cursor is now horizontally flipped for visibility.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The cursor for Teleport, Girder, and homing/strike weapons can now be moved all the way down to water level.\cf1  [Unintentionally, this allowed horizontal girders to be placed partially underwater if the water level was higher than the bottom of the map. See v3.7.2.0 for the fix.]\cf0\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
\cf4\b v3.6.21.2 Beta Update (2004.09.27)\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 The first fix in the list of v3.6.21.1 Fixes was actually a regression for some people not running Windows XP.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}When a player tries to Teleport to a spot that is partially blocked, the cursor is nudged to the nearest available spot and a spangle flashes in the new spot. But in a game with v3.6.21.1 as the logic version (i.e., no emulation) this would only look correct on the local end, while a game was being played. To remote players in a network game, and during playback, the cursor nudge and spangle would not show up.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.19.7: The message \i "Game will take advantage of the latest n.n.n.n features and bug fixes"\i0  will now display the game logic version rather than the exe version.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Speed / update rate\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 Bug introduced in v3.6.21.1: A check was inadvertently disabled, the purpose of which was to prevent the clock from ticking more than 1/4 second during a chunk of "screen lag". It is now re-enabled.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.19.7: During an instant replay, a fast-forward that was fast enough to drop frames could overshoot the end of the turn, eating into the turn time of the next Worm.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}v3.6.21.1 restricted the rendering rate from dropping below 10 fps. This was too arbitrary. The frame drop threshold is now calculated as a point of diminishing returns, where further frame dropping would not boost the speed by more than 10%. When fast-forwarding, this is often well above 10 fps, especially on faster computers (this should also make screen lag more tolerable). Additionally, slow computers may sometimes need to drop below 10 fps (for example, when a lot of fire is being thrown around).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}In-game palette fading is smoother now. This is accomplished by two changes: streamlining the way fading is done (previously, each fade increment was done separately for objects, water and terrain), and making external applications unaware of the game's palette adjustments. (The latter is a workaround for that fact that, regarding palettes, DirectDraw does not give exclusive treatment to full-screen apps.)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 Volume adjustments (introduced in v3.6.19.7)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 When the volume was adjusted in the front end, and a game was started within the same session, the adjustment would be forgotten.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Volume adjustments in the front end are now instantly applied to the ambient "menu loop".\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The volume setting was not being applied to the "loading tick" sound effect (made each time the pie chart fills by an extra 4%)\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
\b\fs24 Changes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 For readability, the Extract Log feature now uses "\f4\bullet\bullet\bullet\f0 " to denote game events rather than "\f4 ****\f0 " as before.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
\cf4\b v3.6.21.3 Beta Update (2004.09.28)\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 In v3.6.21.2, the in-game palette would not be restored after minimising in most circumstances.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}On systems running Windows 9x/ME, W:A v3.6.21.2 would crash when a game was started. Due to this, the DirectDraw palette workaround will be disabled on those systems.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The following v3.6.21.2 fix was incomplete and is now fixed as intended: \i "When the volume was adjusted in the front end, and a game was started within the same session, the adjustment would be forgotten."\i0\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
\cf4\b v3.6.22.1 Beta Update (2004.10.06)\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 Volume adjustments (introduced in v3.6.19.7)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 If the volume was adjusted in-game, the change didn't have an instant effect upon returning to the front end.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Volume adjustment is now applied to streams and in-game ambient music. There is now nothing left that doesn't respond to volume control.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.21.1: The Extract Log feature brings up a console window to show its progress. However, it would often be opened behind other windows. It will now try to move itself to the front. \cf1 [Note: This fix did not in fact work.]\cf0\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Bugs introduced in v3.6.21.2\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 WAgame files made by private betas before 2004-01-27, or Mission/Training from any version, would crash upon playback. The former would in some cases play without crashing, but would desync due to differing crate falls.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}If W:A were forced to minimise in-game (without using the Escape menu option) then its palette would be garbled and no amount of minimising would bring it back.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The game would sometimes crash when returning to the front end.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 Fixes affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 The Girder Starter-Pack allows you to select a stop sign after placing at least one girder, to prematurely stop placing them. However, in v3.5 Beta 1, this was inadvertently disabled. It works again now.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
\b\fs24 Features\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 The <center> tag is now supported and used in ServerList.htm.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The Extract Log feature now lists total turn/retreat times for each team.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The colour scheme used for allies (red, blue, green, yellow, purple, cyan) can now be modified to allow those with certain types of colour deficiency to be able to easily distinguish problematic colour pairs. (It is targeted particularly towards protanomaly.) This switch has been added to the Options menu, replacing the terrain editing button in that screen. If the new colour set does not help you and you still have trouble distinguishing certain team colours, please post in the support forum \cf1\b (see section 7.0).\cf0\b0\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Features affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 You now get retreat time after using the Girder Starter-Pack on land.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The Mortar and Homing Missile now have shiny new launchers that are coloured differently, to make them easily distinguishable from the Bazooka and Homing Pigeon. The Bazooka also has a makeover.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
\b\fs24 Notes\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\b0\fs20 Due to the changes regarding colours, a pair of new sprite archives have been included in this release. These files are approximately 12 MB each, and are not internally compressed because this allows the distributed package to compress much better (for a quicker download).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}If you are not going to use the colour deficiency option, you may safely delete Gfx1.dir, freeing 12 MB of hard disk space. Similarly, you may delete Gfx0.dir. Deleting them both will still allow W:A to run, but will locally disable the new colour features.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The original Gfx.dir is still used for compatibility purposes. Do not delete it.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Due to the larger sprite archive, W:A now requires 8 MB more RAM than before. If this is a problem for you, please post in the support forum \cf1\b (see section 7.0).\cf0\b0\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}As an upshot, W:A may be slightly faster in-game since it will not need to decompress sprites on the fly.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
\cf4\b v3.6.23.0 Beta Update (2005.03.23)\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 There were quotation typos in two sets of localised in-game text comments. These could cause a crash when the game tried to display the erroneous text.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\cf8\b Worm Death on Land / Spanish\cf0\b0 : Every time a worm died on land there was at most a 1/38 chance that the game would crash if localised in Spanish.\par
\cf8\b{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Worm Sickness / non-English\cf0\b0 : Every time a worm got sick (due to a Skunk, an Indian Nuclear Test, or a Nuke at Sudden Death) there was at most a 1/16 chance that the game would crash if localised in a language other than English.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Whether or not a crash would actually happen depended on the layout of RAM, the compiled executable, and random chance. In certain versions of the executable, there may have been no chance of a crash from one or both of these bugs. However, even if there was no crash, the erroneous comment, when displayed, would be a concatenation of two particular comments which would never be individually displayed. For example, if a Worm named Torg died on land, and the Spanish bug occurred without a crash, the comment "Torg falleci\'f3 ya no pod\'eda m\'e1s" would be displayed.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The fix involved changing which comments are randomly chosen; previously there had been two comments in a set which were treated as one. When emulating previous logic versions, the bug will be re-enacted without a crash, by joining the two comments with an '&' character. This guarantees that any two given players will see the same comment at the same time if W:A is localised in the same language for both of them.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.19.7: If your nation in \b Control Panel: Regional and Language Options: Location\b0  was unrecognised, you were assigned an invalid flag number and thus disallowed from joining hosted games (not to mention being greeted with several error messages regarding defaults upon launching W:A). Now when your nation is unrecognised, you are assigned a question-mark flag and can join any game (and fanfare, flag and soundbank will default to the UK for CPU and newly-created teams).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Flags that were partially black became partially transparent in the host/join screens.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The German W:A CD-ROM had some erroneous Mission Image files, causing certain missions to play with the wrong map. W:A now works around this bug by using the duplicate images from elsewhere on the CD-ROM.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Domain names are now supported and used in ServerList.htm. (Previously, only IP addresses would work.) Also, the default http port is now always 80, and doesn't have to be specified explicitly in a server list with multiple servers.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}At some point around 2002-09-10, the WormNET server incorrectly started limiting nicknames to 15 characters instead of 16, such that if you came onto WormNET with a 16 character name, it would be truncated and you would not be able to properly join channels. W:A now detects and recognises the truncated name as being your own. When you host or join a game, your name will not be truncated.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.22.1: Changing the team colour set in the Options menu only lasted for a single session; it was necessary to change the registry setting directly to make it stick.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Bug in a feature introduced in v3.5 Beta 1: Entering a line nearly 500 characters long in the host/join chat caused a local crash. Besides fixing this, the maximum line length has also been changed from 512 to 500 characters.\cf1  [After this fix it was still possible for long lines to cause a local crash. See v3.6.28.0 for the complete fix.]\cf0\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Bug introduced in v3.6.19.7: When using the mouse to open the Scheme or Terrain combo-boxes, if there had been no previously selected item or if it had been modified, the first item in the list would be autoselected.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Map Editor\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.19.7: PNG levels saved with indestructible borders, when loaded, would be reset to having no borders.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}A corrupt or invalid .BIT file would cause a crash when loaded.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}When an image larger than 1920\'d7696 (horizontally, vertically or both) was loaded with the Import function, it was automatically resized to 1920\'d7696 without prompting the user. Now the user is prompted to choose between Shrinking and Cropping.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.21.1: As noted in the entry for v3.6.22.1, the Extract Log console window sometimes opened behind other windows. The previous fix did not work. A stronger attempt is now made to bring the window to the foreground. Also, it now displays the timer on one line instead of scrolling.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Bug introduced in v3.6.19.7: The blank/duplicate name detection of the Team Editor was broken. It works properly now.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.20.1: When scrolling the display while paused in Single Step mode, the camera coordinates were allowed to bypass the normal limits. The display didn't scroll beyond the edges, but you had to mouse back the same distance you had "virtually" moved beyond the edges to be able to scroll again.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Bug introduced in v3.6.20.1: Missing checksums were not reported during playback.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Fixes affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 At a certain water level, Donor Cards would float, throwing the game into an endless loop (the previous fix applied only to Weapon/Utility/Health Crates and Oil Drums).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}When a Worm was in a confined space, its Ninja Rope would sometimes fail to catch for no apparent reason. (Note that this has nothing to do with the fact that the rope will not catch if you are right against a wall; this remains the same.) In free space, the worm would always be shifted approximately one pixel up and to the left every time the rope caught, regardless of the direction in which the rope pointed.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Changes affecting sound/speech (strictly speaking these changes don't affect the game logic, but they are tied to the logic version so that all players will hear the same thing)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 In the Russian speech bank, the "Collect" sound was missing the initial sound effect.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
\b\fs24 Features\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 The Intro fade-in screens (Team17 and Microprose logos) have been improved.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The nation flags are improved in the WormNET lobby, with an expanded palette. In the host/join screens however, they cannot use an expanded palette, as it's already taken by the map thumbnail; so in there, they have not changed as much.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Flags have been added for the countries \cf4 Chile\cf0 , \cf4 Serbia\cf0 , and \cf4 Slovenia\cf0 . Currently these flags work only in the WormNET lobby, not in the host/join screen.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The Server List now includes a link that automatically logs you onto WormNET using the nickname entered in the main Network Menu (this works because logins are currently not enabled).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}You are now allowed to input all the characters allowed by the WormNET server that parse straightforwardly and are included in W:A's font:\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 Nicknames \emdash  Characters \cf4 A\cf0 -\cf4 Z\cf0 , \cf4 a\cf0 -\cf4 z\cf0 , \cf4 0\cf0 -\cf4 9\cf0 , \cf4 -`\cf0\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Game Names \emdash  Characters \cf4 A\cf0 -\cf4 Z\cf0 , \cf4 a\cf0 -\cf4 z\cf0 , \cf4 0\cf0 -\cf4 9\cf0 , \cf4 !$%()*,-./:;=?@[]^_`\{|\}~\'a3\'c0\'c1\'c2\'c3\'c4\'c5\'c6\'c7\'c8\'c9\'ca\'cb\'cc\'cd\'ce\'cf\'d0\'d1\'d2\'d3\'d4\'d5\'d6\'d7\'d8\'d9\'da\'db\'dc\'dd\'de\'9f\'df\'e0\'e1\'e2\'e3\'e4\'e5\'e6\'e7\'e8\'e9\'ea\'eb\'ec\'ed\'ee\'ef\'f0\'f1\'f2\'f3\'f4\'f5\'f6\'f7\'f8\'f9\'fa\'fb\'fc\'fd\'fe\'ff\'bf\'a1\cf0\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 The <font> tag works a bit more nicely in ServerList.htm, which has been modified accordingly. Specifically, if the size is in quotes (e.g. <font size="2">) the sizes 1-4 are sorted by true size. And colour names (e.g. <font color="yellow">) are supported.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Two new text colour escape codes have been added: \\k for black and \\R for dark red. These work in the same places as the other colour escape codes (ygwrnbBpP).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The red colour used for WormNET join/quit notifications is now darker, unless the alternative (protanomaly) colour set is used.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Changes to in-game AFK mode (triggered by entering /afk or /away in the in-game chat)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 If enabled during worm placement, the worm will be automatically teleported to a random spot.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}If enabled while on the Rope, Bungee, Parachute or Jet Pack, the worm will dismount if necessary before skipping its turn.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 The Extract Log feature now reports user fuse/herd/bounce for each weapon firing, when applicable.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Changed the frame-drop speed ratio from 10% to 33%. (During fast-forwarding of a replay it will still be 10%.) This should make "screen lag" a bit less disruptive, and is a stopgap until a better method for tempering screen lag is found.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Pressing the \b R\b0  key during playback of a recorded game will restart it from the beginning. This is useful if you are fast forwarding and have overshot the part you wanted to see.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The in-game dialog box (ESC) and chat (PageDown/PageUp) transitions now always happen at a smooth default speed, independent of fast forward, slow motion and single step. The scrolling of chat text happens at normal speed except in fast forward, where it speeds up.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The \b Delete\b0  key now skips past the minimum info detail level when worms are invincible.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Features affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 Changes affecting sound/speech (strictly speaking these changes don't affect the game logic, but they are tied to the logic version so that all players will hear the same thing)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 When a delayed weapon becomes activated, the "Drop" speech is now used. (Previously, "Collect" was used for both for this and for collecting crates, and "Drop" was never used.) \par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}When a Worm found itself near a fused weapon about to explode, it would be alarmed and randomly say either "RunAway", "TakeCover", or "WhatThe". There was another sound also intended to be used for this purpose, "Grenade", but it was left unused due to a typo. Now it is used.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
