\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  The update is now distributed as a self-contained installer. Notable characteristics of the installer are:\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 Automatic detection of Worms Armageddon's install location;\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Detection of common mistakes, such as attempting to update the TryMedia version or previous installation a Beta update before installing the v3.0 Patch;\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}User data preservation: the installer will keep customised settings and teams, schemes, saved levels, replays, etc., contrary to what was done in the v3.0.5.0 Beta installer and v3.0 Patch;\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Automatic download and installation of prerequisites (requires a working Internet connection): the v3.0 Patch and GFX archive updates (introduced in v3.6.22.1) are downloaded as needed from Team17's FTP server ( \cf4\ul ftp://ftp.team17.com/pub/t17/patches/pc/\cf0\ulnone  ).\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Registry scripts that change game options have been moved to a new \b Tweaks\b0  folder.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC, CS]\fs20  Limitations relaxed or removed\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC, CS]\fs20  It is now possible to play on PNG maps having dimensions other than 1920\'d7696. A cavern map may now be up to 32504 pixels wide or 32600 pixels tall; an island is limited to being 28408 wide or 30552 tall. The minimum map size is 640\'d732. A map's width and height must be divisible by 8.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 In the network join screen, the game now displays a warning message when it begins receiving a map file larger than 512 kB. Also, if the map is a colour PNG, and the image area (width \'d7 height) is larger than 8 megapixels, the game will require confirmation from the user to load the map once it has been received. The warning limit for the map's area can be overridden by creating a value named "\b MapAreaWarnLimit\b0 " of type REG_DWORD in W:A's Options key (HKEY_CURRENT_USER\\Software\\Team17SoftwareLTD\\WormsArmageddon\\Options), which specifies the image area threshold, above which the game asks for a confirmation before loading the image. You can quickly set this value to the default value or disable the warning by importing \b MapAreaWarnLimit_Default.reg\b0  or \b MapAreaWarnLimit_Unlimited.reg\b0  (from the \b Tweaks\b0  folder) respectively.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}If you are using \b Wine\b0 , large map support may not work properly without the NoLandInVram workaround. See \b Fixes\b0 , above.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  There is no longer any upper limit imposed on the choice of in-game resolution (previously it was limited to 1920\'d71440).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  It is now possible to play with up to \b 48\b0  Worms if all players are using v3.6.28.0 or later. Because of limitations in the network protocol of older W:A versions, if the total exceeds \b 18\b0  Worms, clients using older versions will be shown only 1 Worm in each team and the game will not be allowed to start. Note that most randomly generated 1920\'d7696 maps will not accommodate 48 worms without forcing manual placement, unless the host modifies the map to have lots of Placement Holes (see below).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Map Editor, you may now fine-tune the number of Placement Holes instead of being constrained to either 0 or 18. This is done by left- or right-clicking the circled-girder icon, which displays the current number of Holes; holding \b Shift\b0  allows you to fine tune the value, otherwise it skips from 0 to 18 to 32 to 48 and then to the maximum. The allowed range is 0-300, but hosting a game with more than 18 Holes requires all players to be using v3.6.28.0 or later. If a map is too small to accommodate the requested number of holes, the value will max out; for example, a solid 640\'d7480 map can't have more than 8-13 holes, depending on its random seed; but if it maxes out at 10, further Reseeds will be limited to 10 Holes (and eventually as few as 8) unless you manually increment the count. Holding \b Ctrl\b0  while clicking Reseed will force it to try for as many Holes as it can get.\cf1  [Due to a bug in v3.6.28.0, the maximum number of Placement Holes was actually 255; any higher number was truncated (equivalent to subtracting 256). See \b Fixes\b0  under \b v3.7.0.0 Update\b0 .]\cf0\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  It is now possible to customise the initial number of in-game hazard objects (Mines and Oil Drums). The setting can be adjusted in the Scheme Options editor by Shift+clicking the Mine/Oil Drum button. The maximum number is \b 250\b0 , however this is limited by the rule which forbids two objects from being initially placed too close to each other.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  Games can now be started with just one team, or with teams of just one allied colour. In such cases, the game will only end in a draw (when all teams surrender or are eliminated). This works for both "multiplayer" and "online" games. When an online game is started without anyone else joining, it will act like an offline game.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  W:A launching / command line parameters\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  People hosting Direct IP games may now offer links in the format \b wa://address-of-host\b0 , and launching this link will cause W:A to automatically launch and join the hosted game. This link format supports additional parameters \b (See Footnote 3)\b0 . A port can be specified using the \b wa://ip:port\b0  syntax.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The command line "\b WA.exe /host\b0 " will cause W:A to automatically launch and host a Direct IP game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The \b /play\b0  parameter required to play replays is now optional, as long as the replay has a \b .WAgame\b0  file extension. This allows associating .WAgame files with WA.exe directly.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The \b /playat\b0  parameter will now accept the starting time as an argument in the command line, bypassing the dialog box. With this parameter, playback starts paused. The syntax is: \b WA.exe /playat "\cf4 filename\cf0 .WAgame"\b0  \cf4\b time\cf0\b0\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Minimising\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  While the game is minimised, it will flash its taskbar button and produce a standard beep in the following circumstances:\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 At the start of a local player's turn\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li1260 If the player has gone "away" using the /away or /afk command, the game will only produce a standard beep\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 When the user receives a private whisper\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  The game can now be minimised from both the front end and in-game by pressing \b Shift+Escape\b0 .\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  In-game\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  It is now possible to paste from the clipboard in the in-game chat, using \b Ctrl+V\b0  or \b Shift+Insert\b0 . Several other editing hotkeys have been added: \b Ctrl+Left\b0  and \b Ctrl+Right\b0  move the cursor word by word, \b Ctrl+Delete\b0  deletes the word starting at the cursor, and \b Ctrl+Backspace\b0  deletes the word before the cursor.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC, CS]\fs20  The \b Home\b0  key, which centres on the currently active Worm, now works regardless of whether it is your turn or not. When held down, it now maintains this centring continuously. The key has no effect during others' turns if the current worm is invisible.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Holding \b Shift\b0  now causes the mouse sensitivity to be multiplied by \b 4\b0 . Holding the middle mouse button does the same. With both combined, the multiplier becomes \b 16\b0 . This is useful (sometimes even necessary) when playing on a very large map.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If \b M\b0  is pressed during playback, the current frame will be marked as if "Playback at" had been used. Subsequently pressing \b R\b0  will fast-forward to that point after restarting the replay. As before, \b Shift\b0 +\b R\b0  resets the marker to the first frame of the replay. The marker is temporary and lasts only for the duration of the current playback session.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  During a game, players may now use \b Ctrl+PageDown\b0  to initiate "chat pinning", in which the chat panel is displayed even when it is not "in focus". This allows a player to play while reading what the other players are saying. Since this could give users of v3.6.28.0+ an unfair advantage in situations where there is emulation, in online games with more than 2 players its absence is emulated.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The network chat panel can now be resized using \b Ctrl+Up\b0  and \b Ctrl+Down\b0 . The position is remembered independently for the panel's active and pinned states, but only for the duration of the game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Cursor movement within the weapon panel, and the sliding of the panel when it is opened and closed, is now smooth (as opposed to being updated only 50 times per second).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The player colour swatches in the right side of the in-game chat box are now slightly wider.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  The \b Pause\b0  screenshot key now works in the front end.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If you have achieved a Gold Medal in a mission, you can now adjust the number of Attempts by left- or right-clicking the number. (A higher number of Attempts generally adds items and/or events to a mission to make it easier.)\cf1  [This feature was accidentally disabled in v3.6.28.0. See \b Features\b0  under \b v3.6.29.0 Beta Update\b0 .]\cf0\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The exact values of the Turn Time, Retreat Time, Round Time, Worm Energy and Health Crate Energy settings are now precisely displayed in all screens of the front end and can be fine-tuned. To adjust them in increments of 1, hold the \b Shift\b0  key while left- or right-clicking to increase or decrease the value. Without Shift being held, these settings will cycle through a set of values similarly to how they used to.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 The Round Time is normally measured in minutes, however it can also be adjusted up to 128 seconds in steps of 1 second. The way this is done is a little strange \emdash  you need to go below 0 minutes, and then left- and right-clicking will have a "backwards" effect on the number of seconds.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Various actions involving map rendering, such as clicking a map thumbnail to cycle through randomly generated maps or re-rendering a map preview in the Map Editor, will now be a bit more responsive. The progress indicator \emdash  a small flat piechart (not to be confused with the 3D piechart that shows during the loading of a game) \emdash  has been removed. It was never very meaningful anyway, and may possibly be reimplemented in a future version.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The quick description messages in the front end and some in-game text can be made to use a larger font, to improve accessibility. To enable this feature, import \b LargerFonts_On.reg\b0  (from the \b Tweaks\b0  folder) into your system registry.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the "\b Playback at...\b0 " entry box, you may now use shortcuts such as "3:" instead of "3:00" for 3 minutes, or "1::" instead of "1:00:00" for 1 hour. Before, the best shortcuts for those were "3:0" and "1:0:0".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Using the "\b Playback at...\b0 " entry box, it is now possible to start playback in paused (single-step) mode.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Maps from OnlineWorms (Korean, Japanese, and Chinese Worms) and WWP Aqua (Korean) can now be loaded from W:A's Map Editor. The \b land*.dat\b0  files must be placed underneath \b User\\SavedLevels\b0  and are loaded just like other maps.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 Note that WWP Aqua's maps use a full palette of 256 colours. The Map Editor will allow you to load them with the full palette intact, but exiting forces the map to be dithered to 113 colours so that it will be usable in-game.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  W:A now auto-detects the user's IP address using a reply from the WormNET server. This should make manually configuring the external IP address unnecessary in most cases. The IP address can still be overridden using the "Force IP address" checkbox.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Background gradients are now rendered by the game. When a PNG map with more than 96 colours is used, this now replaces the old behaviour of not having a background at all. The gradient is dithered and may include colours from the map's palette; if a 112 colour map is used, the gradient will \i only\i0  use colours from the map's palette.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  In case of an unrecoverable error, W:A will save an error report to the file \b errorlog.txt\b0 , and a minidump to \b crash.dmp\b0 .\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Host/Join screens, entering "\b /v\b0 ", "\b /ver\b0 ", or "\b /versions\b0 " will display the game logic versions of all players currently present.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A rudimentary host/join chat logging feature has been added. Currently, this logs the hosting and joining of games, the player list upon joining, the chat, players joining and leaving, players kicked (in the host's log), and games initiated. GMT timestamps are included for each log entry, and in the filenames of the logs. The logs are stored in \b User\\Logs\b0 .\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC, CS]\fs20  Flags\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC, CS]\fs20  Flags have been added for seven additional countries for a total of eleven. Extended flags now include \cf4 Chile\cf0 , \cf4 Serbia\cf0 , \cf4 Slovenia\cf0 , \cf4 Lebanon\cf0 , \cf4 Moldova\cf0 , \cf4 Ukraine\cf0 , \cf4 Latvia\cf0 , \cf4 Slovakia\cf0 , \cf4 Costa Rica\cf0 , \cf4 Estonia\cf0 , and \cf4 China\cf0 .\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Extended nation flags are now shown in the host/join screen and in WormNET's list of hosted games.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Previously implemented "test versions" can now be accessed. These are game logic versions which, when emulated, enable some options that are not yet official. If you are hosting a game, you may enable and disable the test versions using commands entered into the chat (see below). The game will then explain this mode change to all players present. Newly joining players will be informed if one of these modes is enabled. These modes persist both through multiple rounds and when the host clicks "Play Again". They are mutually exclusive (enabling one will disable others), although TestStuff is a superset of BattyRope. Access to the options enabled by these test versions should not be considered official at this time, as they are planned to be added to the scheme format (among many other new options that may be more useful) and will then be individually selectable, whereas in test versions they are grouped together and attached to a specific game logic version.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\tx1800 BattyRope:\tab Toggled by entering "\b /batty\b0 " in the chat. Allows the Ninja Rope to stay connected during other players' turns, and also forces Rope Knocking to be enabled.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}150% Speed:\tab Toggled by entering "\b /150\b0 ", "\b /fast\b0 " or "\b /speed\b0 " in the chat. Makes everything in-game go 50% faster; the engine's frame rate is changed from 50 fps to 75 fps.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}TestStuff5:\tab Toggled by entering "\b /ts\b0 " or "\b /test\b0 " in the chat. Enables BattyRope, Rope Knocking, use of weapons during a rope roll, the Indian Rope Trick, worm selection without ending hot seat time, and skipwalking facilitation (up/down/middle arrow keys act like right-clicking while walking); disables loss of control while roping; doubles the maximum speed for roping and jetpacking, and abolishes the speed limit for projectile motion. Also enables Circular Aiming and Anti-lock Power.\cf1  [TestStuff was supposed to include Girder Radius Assist as well, but this feature was accidentally disabled.]\cf0\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  It is now possible to set the TCP port used for hosting games. This setting is in the Network Configuration screen, and affects both WormNET and Direct IP games. Games hosted on a port other than the default one, \b 17011\b0 , will be inaccessible to game versions prior to 3.6.28.0.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Adjustments to previous features\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Right-clicking the Water Level bar in the Map Editor sets the appropriate level for "water drops". However, since the water level is still stored as a percentage, "water drops" are only achievable at certain map heights. At other heights, right-clicking the Water Level bar will result in a "can't click here" beep.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Export Log additions\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Instances of the "alien" glitch are now logged. (This is where a Worm horizontally hitting a wall at a nearly vertical angle steeper than 87.138\'b0 (slope=20) and a vertical speed past the fall damage threshold will stop and twang as if it hit the ground, but will then continue to fall. If the worm fell from a rope dismount, it will not lose control of its turn.)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  Features affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  Players may now view the weapon panel for their team at any time, including during other players' turns. (Strictly speaking this change doesn't affect the game logic, but it is tied to the logic version for fairness.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Chat pinning \emdash  see above. (Strictly speaking this change doesn't affect the game logic, but it is tied to the logic version for fairness.)\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
