\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  Hardware and Operating System compatibility\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Windows 98/ME compatibility, which was accidentally broken in v3.6.29.0, has been restored.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Minimisation support in the front end in Windows Vista was incomplete (upon restoring, it was not possible to interact with UI elements using the mouse).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A now uses a new method of restoring the palette, which has been found to be more effective on Windows Vista and Windows 7. Should the display palette become corrupted, the user can try to restore it manually in-game by pressing \b Shift+Pause\b0 .\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  A new compatibility setting for \b Wine\b0  has been added, \b Force Wine virtual desktop\b0  (ForceWineVirtualDesktop_On.reg). When this setting is enabled, W:A will automatically relaunch itself in a virtual desktop, by running \ldblquote explorer "/desktop=640x480,Worms Armageddon" [\i WA.exe's full command-line\i0 ] /novirtualdesktop\rdblquote . (The /novirtualdesktop switch is used to temporarily override the effect of the setting, thus preventing W:A from entering into an endless loop.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  A new compatibility setting for \b Wine\b0  has been added, \b Use desktop window\b0  (FrontendUseDesktopWindow_Enable.reg). Enabling this setting causes W:A to use the desktop window for the DirectDraw SetCooperativeLevel call, which fixes front end display problems when running under Wine. Note that enabling this option may prevent minimisation during the game from working - Wine users are advised to use a virtual desktop instead.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When W:A v3.6.30.0 or later is run under Wine for the first time, it will offer to enable Wine-specific compatibility settings (ForceWineVirtualDesktop, LandInVram_Disable, SlowFrontendWorkaround_Off and FrontendUseDesktopWindow_Enable).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A's associations are now registered automatically by the Beta Update installer. This means it is no longer necessary to run W:A at least once as Administrator after installing a new Beta Update.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A new compatibility setting has been added, \b Enable double buffering\b0  (enabled by default). Disabling this setting resolves in-game flickering problems under VMware.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When W:A v3.6.30.0 or later is run under VMware for the first time, it will offer to enable VMware-specific compatibility settings (InGameDoubleBuffering_Disable, SlowFrontendWorkaround_Off and FrontendUseVRAM_Disable).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In VMware, tab stops in the front end were not being activated by default.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When W:A v3.6.30.0 or later is run under VirtualBox for the first time, it will offer to enable VirtualBox-specific compatibility settings (SlowFrontendWorkaround_Off and FrontendUseVRAM_Enable).\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Slow front end workaround\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  There are some video cards/drivers under which \b SlowFrontendWorkaround_On.reg\b0  does not fix W:A's "slow front end" lag. It has been found that "SlowFrontendWorkaround_AntiFlicker" fixed the problem in at least one of these cases (with a GeForce 8800GTS 512MB). To reflect the wider use of this version of the slow front end workaround, it has been renamed. It is now enabled by importing \b SlowFrontendWorkaround_Alternative.reg\b0  (from the \b Tweaks\b0  folder) into the system registry, or by selecting the \b Alternative\b0  setting on the Advanced Options screen. Also, \b SlowFrontendWorkaround_On\b0  is now the default mode that W:A will assume if none of the SlowFrontendWorkaround tweaks have been imported into the registry. Note that the Alternative mode will most likely use the maximum CPU of one system core, whereas On and Off modes have lower CPU usage.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Previously, enabling SlowFrontendWorkaround would break the intro fade (assuming /nointro was not used). Now, it is temporarily disabled to make the fade work properly.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  An effect which was previously toggled by the SlowFrontendWorkaround setting is now available as a separate option: \b FrontendUseVRAM_Disable.reg\b0 . This prevents W:A from using video memory in the front end, which may improve compatibility on certain systems.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  Timer workaround\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  On some system configurations, the high-resolution timer would occasionally skip backwards by a minuscule amount, which caused W:A to enter a nearly-infinite loop (if the \b TimerWorkaround_On.reg\b0  tweak wasn't being used). W:A now checks for this condition and prevents a lock-up from happening.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.28.0: On some systems with multiple CPU cores, the weapon panel would not open and close properly. When the mouse was moved, the panel would go "wandering" randomly, eventually going off the side of the screen, sometimes coming back later. This was a very rare but consistently reproducible bug on some systems. If you experienced this bug, it is still recommended that you enable the timer workaround (either using the Advanced Options front end screen, or by importing \b TimerWorkaround_On.reg\b0 , from the \b Tweaks\b0  folder, into your system registry) because the same timer issue that caused the dancing weapon panel bug can also cause screen lag (irregular, jumpy passage of time within the game).\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Keyboard hotkeys & character tables\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Entering international characters not present in W:A's character table sometimes incorrectly resulted in Cyrillic characters. \par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  It was not possible to enter some international characters in the front end due to W:A interpreting some Ctrl+Alt+... keystrokes as Ctrl+... keyboard shortcuts.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The Utility key is now determined based on the keyboard OEM scan code, which should not change across typical system configurations. The previous method, introduced in v3.6.28.0, used the key that generates the \cf4 `\cf0  character on the U.S. English keyboard layout, but required this layout to be installed on the user's PC.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC, CS]\fs20  Mouse input\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  When moving the mouse cursor directly from one hyperlink to another, the highlighted hyperlink was not updated.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A bug in v3.6.29.0 caused the mouse cursor to jump (319,399) pixels down-right at the beginning of every game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Another bug introduced in v3.6.29.0 also caused the mouse cursor to jump. This happened if the chat box was opened during an offline game session (a feature introduced in v3.6.29.0) while a Worm was being manually placed or aiming a Teleport/Girder/homing weapon. Any mouse motion occurring while the chat box was open would be stored up, and when the chat was closed, the mouse cursor would jump.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A bug introduced in v3.6.28.0 caused the camera to be horizontally locked when emulating v3.0 in a cavern terrain.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  While holding the middle mouse button to speed up cursor movement in-game, right-clicking to open the weapon panel would cause the status of the middle button to be forgotten.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  Sound effects\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  The front end ambient sound loop was not being played when the game was started with the \b wa://\b0  or \b /host\b0  command-line parameters.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Due to a bug introduced in v3.6.29.0, it was possible for in-game looped sound effects (such as the Dynamite fuse and the Mole Bomb's digging) to be stopped prematurely when other sounds were played. This was more likely to happen on some systems than others, depending on how quickly the DirectSound backend detected the finishing of a sound being played (the more lag, the less likely the bug).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The stereo panning effect was not applied to sounds when the camera was moved while the game was in single-step mode.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  On systems with a configured nation not explicitly recognised by W:A, a flag, fanfare and soundbank was not being selected for intrinsic teams and default values.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Fanfares for nations not explicitly recognised by W:A will now default to "Simple", in conformance with nations explicitly recognised by W:A but not having an appropriate nation fanfare.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The "Russian" soundbank is no longer selected by default for Croatia.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Subfolder support for schemes and maps now works more cleanly\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Clicking subfolders no longer changes the name in the edit box.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When entering a folder with the keyboard (Enter key), the first file is now selected by default.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Pressing Enter or clicking on a file directly after it has already been loaded will now reload the file if its timestamp or size has changed; otherwise it will close the drop-down list box as before.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Subfolders with names beginning in ".." are no longer hidden.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC, CS]\fs20  Schemes\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Loaded schemes no longer have the ".wsc" extension added to them in the combo edit box.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  After deleting a scheme in the offline multiplayer screen, the text in the scheme selection drop-down wasn't being updated despite the fact that the game loaded the Intermediate scheme.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When saving a scheme in a subfolder, the overwrite confirmation dialog box would incorrectly be displayed if a scheme with the same filename existed in the main Schemes folder. No confirmation dialog box would appear when overwriting a scheme in a subfolder.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When attempting to delete a scheme that didn't exist, the delete confirmation dialog box showed up anyway, implying that the file existed.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Options Menu, the scheme edit box now scrolls for long scheme filenames. It also has more room to show the scheme name below the edit box.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Loading a scheme with "random worm order" correctly updated the required version, so that players with a version not supporting that feature would be crosshatched in red in the host's player list. However, if the host toggled this feature directly using the Worm Select button, the required version was not updated. This meant that a game could be started that was supposed to have random worm order but didn't, or alternatively that a player could be falsely flagged as being unable to play, preventing the game from being started.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Loading an intrinsic scheme (such as Intermediate) did not update the required version. This meant that if the scheme beforehand was unsupported by any players present, their names would continue to be crosshatched in red even though intrinsic schemes are supported by all versions of W:A going back to v3.0.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  WormNET\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  The WormNET IRC client has been made more conformant to the IRC standard.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A would sometimes fail to reply to IRC PING messages with a PONG, and would time out should there be no outgoing traffic for several minutes.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When getting kicked or banned from WormNET, W:A will now display an appropriate message (including the moderator-specified reason), instead of a generic disconnection message.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Sometimes lines containing colour codes weren't being wrapped correctly in WormNET chat.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 The fix for this issue caused some changes in the way HTML was displayed. The file ServerList.htm has been updated to display correctly on all W:A versions.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  WormNET private message formatting codes are now parsed and displayed for sent messages.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  In the WormNET, host/join and LAN lobbies, wrapped lines of chat could become partially obscured when the scroll bar was created.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The Snooper detection, introduced in v3.6.29.0, now ignores spaces in the "version" field.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Clients not having a valid IRC "real name" field will no longer be displayed with an UK flag. The "UK" two-letter country code, popularised by 3rd-party applications, is still supported but is deprecated (the correct ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 code is "GB").\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Received IRC private actions are now displayed correctly (these can only be sent using a snooper or IRC client at the moment).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A no longer automatically replies to any special messages (such as CTCPs) sent to WormNET channels.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  A scrollbar was sometimes incorrectly placed on the WormNET channel list screen.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC, CS]\fs20  Host / join\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  When hosting, W:A will no longer accept forged chat messages from clients in the host/join screen. It will also forward private messages only to the recipient, thus making host/join whisper spying by clients no longer possible.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  When hosting non-WormNET games, W:A will now check the game ID. This will prevent games hosted via Direct IP to be accidentally joined by players trying to join a stale WormNET game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  The resolution of network timers in the connection dialog box and match finished screen has been increased. This considerably improves the speed of joining games.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If the connection process was cancelled at the wrong moment, you would be left with an hourglass cursor.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When exiting a game that was hosted or joined via "Direct TCP/IP" in the Network Choice screen, you will now be returned to that screen instead of the LAN Lobby.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A would exit silently if it failed to open certain files from the game CD. Now it will display a message and create an error log.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When a player left, it would correctly clear all the other players' light bulbs on the clients' sides; however, on the host's side the light bulbs would remain lit. In the online next round screen, the light bulbs would at least remain synchronised in this situation, but the host's light bulb would stay lit on all sides after a player left (whereas the clients' light bulbs would be cleared).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.19.7: When the host changed maps, each client's light bulb would only be cleared on their own end and on the host's end.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In v3.6.29.0, pressing Tab in the host/join screen would switch from the edit box to the scheme combo box; but once focused on the scheme box, Tab would no longer work.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Kicking\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\fs12 [DC]\fs20  When being kicked by a host using W:A v3.5 or later, a client would usually not process the kick message and would state "The connection to the network has been lost" instead of "The host has removed you from the game." This was a client-side bug and has now been fixed.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When kicking a player, the host did not hear a sound effect. The same went for the player being kicked. Both will now hear the same sound effect that joined players hear when a player leaves, disconnects or is kicked.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  The "INVALID MAP FILE" and "Please wait while the level file loads" notices did not restore after minimising.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If you're a client, minimised while the host clicks "Play Again" or "New Match", you will no longer crash; instead, the game will flash its taskbar button and produce a standard beep. Likewise, the same will now happen if the host starts the game while you're minimised (which is normally not possible).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  If you were disconnected from a network game (due to a network failure or the host quitting), in-game options such as volume and detail level changed during that game weren't saved.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If a host using v3.6.29.0 loaded a scheme that was externally edited to have custom Jet Pack fuel, and the Jet Pack power byte was set to 128 or higher (129 stars or higher; 123 fuel units or higher), and player(s) using an older version were present, the game would silently emulate the old version, with default Jet Pack fuel (30 units), instead of printing the proper error message and highlighting the older-version player(s) in red.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The "Twang1" sound, played when a player disconnects, was used only in the initial host/join screen, not in the next round or match finished screens.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Desynchronisation issues\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\fs12 [DC]\fs20  On some systems, a network game started with an intrinsic map (Cars, Polar, etc.) would desynchronise on the client side when the game was started. The bug was always latent in W:A, but first manifested in v3.6.28.0. There was a workaround in v3.6.29.0 regarding this bug, but it did not fix the desynchronisation.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If a multi-round network game was played on an intrinsic map, and the host did not manually change the map before starting Round 2, the game would desynchronise. The same would happen if a new match was started after one that had been played on an intrinsic map, and the host did not manually change the map before starting the first round of the new match.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Editing certain scheme options in an external scheme editor (or hex-editing the .WSC file directly) could cause problems. In particular, the Sudden Death Water Rise Rate, Mine Fuse, and Fall Damage settings could be edited to normally out-of-range values. However, once the scheme was loaded in W:A, going into the Options Editor would automatically reset the values if they were out of the normal range. If a host went into the Options Editor, the values would be reset, but the Cancel button would be operational \emdash  though using this button would be unexpected when no manual change had been made, and pressing Exit would commit the automatic changes and undo the externally edited options. What was worse was that if a client went into the Options Editor to view the settings, they would be reset on the client's end. This would result in a desynchronisation if a game was started with this scheme.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li1260 Sudden Death Water Rise Rate was reset to Medium (2) if it was anything other than Off (0), Slow (1), Medium (2), or Fast (3). Nonstandard values of this setting change the water rise rate nonlinearly.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Mine Fuse was reset to 3 seconds if it was not 0-3 seconds or Random. Nonstandard values of this setting can go from 5-127 seconds.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Fall Damage was reset to Off (0) if it was not On (1). Nonstandard values of this setting change the strength of the fall damage nonlinearly.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Some other scheme settings were reset to default values if they were out-of-range, but this was not important because the out-of-range values were not special and thus were not commonly used.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC, CS]\fs20  In-game network play\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  A disconnection of a spectator (a "player" with no team) was not noted in the chat box, either during the game or in replay (or exported log).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  W:A would often display a 10-second countdown with the text "Waiting for players" at the end of a network game, waiting for a confirmation network packet that was never sent.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Previous versions of W:A silently discarded front end network packets while in-game. This could cause chat lines to be lost. W:A now queues front end network packets while in-game and processes them when W:A re-enters the front end.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Games with three or more players\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\fs12 [DC]\fs20  A bug in v3.6.29.0 caused all players to desynchronise when one player quit or disconnected, if the disconnection was detected by the host between turns.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Another bug nearly always caused all players to desynchronise when one player quit or disconnected on their first turn. This bug can probably also occur later in the game, but that aspect of it is poorly understood and hard to reproduce (though the fix would apply in that case as well). Note that despite the similarity to the other desynchronisation bug fixed in this Beta Update, this bug dates back to Worms2.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When a client disconnected, the host would see the reason for disconnection but other clients would only see a generic disconnection message. The more detailed disconnection reason (timeout, network drop, desynchronisation) was being recorded, but not displayed.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The disconnection of spectators was not recorded at all by the host.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  In network games, the volume slider in the Escape menu wouldn't slide if it was the local player's turn and the in-game mouse pointer was active (during initial worm placement or if a point-and-click weapon was selected).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The grey progress indicators displayed next to player names during loading will now update more smoothly and responsively.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  More validation is now done on data received over the network.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If, within the same instance of WA.exe, first a game logic version earlier than 3.5 Beta 3pre13 (most likely 3.0 or 3.5 Beta 2) was emulated (i.e. legacy buggy Bungeeing Worm sprite), and then a version of 3.5 Beta 3pre13 or later was emulated (i.e. with the Bungeeing Worm sprite fix) \emdash  or vice versa, the latter first and then the former \emdash  and then a weapon was used while the Bungee was attached, it could cause a desynchronisation.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC, CS]\fs20  Recorded games / replays\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  The passage of game time between turns and after the end of the game is now recorded, like it was before v3.6.19.15. This means that chat messages communicated between turns or after the end of a game will no longer pile up into one frame (unless they were communicated during a period of network lag).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When opening a recorded game that points to an intrinsic map, W:A now verifies that the intrinsic map exists. Previously, if it did not exist, the map from the last game would be used and playback would desynchronise.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  After a fast-forward while playing back a recorded game (either when using the "Playback at" command, or when seeking to a marked position), the chat panel was not updated. If it is open, the chat panel is now also updated during the fast-forward \emdash  if the negligible overhead is undesirable, it can be avoided by closing the chat panel.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The screen capture function had a memory leak. This was most evident when using the Export Video feature, but happened when taking a screenshot as well. Approximately 278 kilobytes were leaked every time a frame was captured. Capturing a very large number of frames (on the order of thousands or more, depending on free RAM) would eventually cause W:A to crash.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Export Log will now print "Game Ends - Alt+F4 pressed" if this is likely to have been the method of quitting, whereas before it would say "Game Ends - End of file" in this case.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  More data validation is now done when playing back recorded game files.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Ever since the identity of the local player was added to the replay file format in v3.6.19.17, the game has tried to detect the local player when playing back older replay files. However, there was a minor bug in the message given when there was more than one spectator and all that could be deduced was that one of them was local.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The v3.6.22.0 threshold drowning worm emulation bug (see v3.6.26.4 fixes) is now detected during playback (and Export Log) in most situations. This prevents a Checksum Mismatch error from being printed in situations where the checksum was actually locally correct.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Messages, strings, and fonts\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  The Blow Torch weapon was named "BlowTorch" in game, breaking consistency with the front end and with Worms2, where it is named "Blow Torch".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Some "Morse Code" messages in Missions were being truncated when displayed in game, in particular some of the messages in the Spanish translation.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The Spanish translation for "cyan" was "azul-verdoso", which has now been replaced with "cian".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Missions screen, one of the mission names was long enough in the Spanish translation to be wrapped into two lines and cropped. The on-screen space for the mission name has been enlarged to rectify this.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The Spanish punctuation marks \cf4\'bf\'a1\cf0  were present in the front end's font set but were not available in-game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Three Spanish messages and one Portuguese message had exclamation mark related errors.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the front end, the three largest fonts no longer crop the bottom pixel row of the lowest-reaching character glyphs.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  Translations\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  In Spanish, Crate Spy has been renamed from "Caja esp\'eda" to "Esp\'eda de cajas" (correction by "OutofOrder").\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  An incorrect character was fixed in the Spanish translation of the Basic Training #8 description text.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  An incorrect character was fixed in the Russian translation of a 2-worm kill comment.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Some Morse code tips in Spanish were missing for Mission 9: "Water Surprise", Mission 14: "Super Sheep to the rescue!", and Mission 20: "Rumble in the Farmyard", with translations provided by "OutofOrder".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Apostrophes in Italian in-game messages were being incorrectly displayed.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The Italian translation in the in-game quit confirmation dialog box incorrectly displayed "S\'c3" instead of "S\'cc".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The \b Russian\b0  translation was updated with corrections from "Shtirlitz".\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  Free RAM & disk space\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  W:A will now display warnings on start-up when the current directory is not writable, or if there is little free disk space on the current drive.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Some minor memory leaks were fixed.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC, CS]\fs20  Miscellaneous\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Some versions of W:A installers would not create the User\\Teams directory, which caused W:A to fail to save the team file. W:A will now create this subdirectory if it doesn't exist.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A would sometimes lock up after creating a console window, which is used to display the progress of operations such as exporting a log.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.23.0: Precise fuse timers, a playback feature added in v3.6.20.1, could not be turned off by cycling through name tags with the \b Delete\b0  key, if Invincibility ("god mode") was enabled in the scheme. \cf1 [This was an incomplete fix; only fuses of missiles/animals were allowed to be turned off \emdash  Mine fuses and Crate contents were still not. See v3.7.0.0 fixes.]\cf0\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In v3.6.19.7, the ability was added to cycle both forward and backwards through randomly generated terrains by clicking and Shift+clicking the maps' thumbnails, respectively. However, the addition of this feature introduced some bugs. It was possible to get trapped in a loop, where only low-detail terrains would be generated, or (rarely) terrains within only one of the templates (e.g., double-cavern, single island, etc.) would be generated. The only way to get out of the loop was to leave that front end screen and come back to it. In v3.6.20.1, this problem was addressed by forcing only maximum-detail terrains to be generated. It was still possible to get trapped in a template loop.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\fs12 [DC]\fs20  The forward and reverse sequence through randomly generated maps was different every time you entered a front end screen in v3.6.19.7 to v3.6.29.0. Now, the map before and after a given map in the Click / Shift+Click sequence will always be the same.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If a map had been loaded through a means other than local clicking (e.g., loaded by a remote host in an online game, or loaded within the Map Editor and then shown as a thumbnail) then the first Click or Shift+Click would leave that map behind, without returning to it. This is now fixed.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Access has been restored to the full range of detail levels available in v3.0 to v3.5 Beta. You will no longer be limited to maps of only maximum detail, as you were starting in v3.6.20.1.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  It is no longer possible to get trapped in a template loop when clicking / Shift+clicking the large map thumbnail.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  There are now 2,147,483,648 available maps in the large thumbnail's cycle, and 2,147,483,648 maps for each template within the Map Editor (i.e., 17,179,869,184 maps). If you were to click 2,147,483,648 times in a row, you'd return to the same map from which you started.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  In the Network Choice screen, the worms' eyes and eyebrows in the LAN and WormNET buttons were transparent.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Team Editor screen, double-clicking the team name's question mark button was supposed to cause all worm names to be randomly generated at once. However, this feature was broken in v3.6.19.7. It has been restored to working order.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When rapidly clicking the "draw holes" or "draw tunnels" buttons in the Map Editor, the same random seed would be used multiple times in a row, changing at most only once per second.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  With the "BattyRope" option enabled (either explicitly or as part of TestStuff), a Worm with its Jet Pack persisting between turns would have its Fuel display overwrite its Health display on screen. Now the Fuel is inserted below the Health.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.19.7: When launching a replay file, W:A would momentarily switch the display mode to 640\'d7480 before switching to the configured in-game resolution. This caused most monitors to go blank briefly, even if the in-game resolution was the same as the Windows desktop resolution.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Taskbar System Menu\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  It is now possible to use the System Menu when minimised from the front end. This menu is opened by right-clicking W:A's Taskbar button. This allows you to Close the game without having to restore it first (in most game modes).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When W:A was minimised during a replay playback session using Alt+Tab or Alt+Esc or some other indirect trigger, right-clicking W:A's Taskbar button crashed the game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The mouse cursor is no longer hidden in the System Menu.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  Crashes\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Pressing \b Escape\b0  in some front end screens (Mission, Training and Deathmatch) caused abnormal minimisation, often followed by a crash.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A would crash when it tried to display the large map size warning while being minimised.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A would crash when the offline multiplayer screen was opened if the previously-loaded map (stored in current.thm) was a .BIT map and was corrupted.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A would crash when it tried to display a message box while being minimised. W:A will now flash its taskbar button and produce a standard beep when this happens, and will display the message box once it's restored.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A bug in v3.6.29.0 caused W:A to crash in some circumstances if an instant replay was skipped by pressing \b Space\b0 .\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A bug in v3.6.29.0 caused W:A to crash upon an instant replay, if one or more crates were present and an earlier version was being emulated \emdash  such as v3.6.28.0[teststuff5], since v3.6.29.0 did not have its own version of TestStuff.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In v3.6.29.0, when emulating v3.0, attempting to use worm selection in a team that started with just 1 worm would crash the game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When W:A is running on some system configurations and a bitmap fails to allocate to video RAM, it will now allocate to system RAM instead of crashing.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Minor/obscure changes have been made that may avoid bitmap-related crashes in the front end.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  It was possible for W:A to crash when the "Please wait... working..." box popped up, when a game was started. This was exceedingly rare, but confirmed to happen at least sometimes under Windows 7.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A would crash when attempting to open the Team Editor if there was a 4-bit BMP image in the User\\Flags or User\\Graves folder. Now it is capable of loading 4-bit BMPs.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A would crash if it failed to load a sound sample from the FESfx subdirectory. It will now display an error message.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A would crash if it tried to display a message after it had exited the full-screen graphics mode, for example if an error occurred upon saving the team file. It will now display the message using a standard Windows message box.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  W:A would crash if the user minimised during the front end's intro sequence.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC, CS]\fs20  Fixes affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  Fatal and potentially fatal bugs\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\fs12 [CS]\fs20  A bug in v3.6.29.0 caused network desynchronisations and checksum errors when the Laser Sight was used. Due to its random nature, this bug cannot be emulated.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In a game with CPU team(s), in which an external scheme editor was used to assign "zero power" to a Mine, Dynamite, Priceless Ming Vase, Air Strike, Napalm Strike, Mail Strike, French Sheep Strike, Mike's Carpet Bomb, MB Bomb, and/or Concrete Donkey, if the CPU AI tried to analyse using one of those weapons, W:A would crash. \b (See Footnote 2.)\b0\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  If a Worm was dropped into a pile of multiple overlapping Worms (from high enough to suffer fall damage), the worm would "hover" briefly the moment it hit the pile. It would actually be accelerating during this "hover", suffering extra fall damage as a result, prolonged more by every extra worm in the pile. In the most extreme case possible, with a 48th worm dropped into an pile of 47 overlapping worms, the game would be thrown into an endless loop.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In a game with "Weapons Don't End Turn" and "Loss of Control Doesnt End Turn" enabled, if a Worm was releasing a herd of Mad Cows, and was fatally injured (most likely by one of the cows) at the same 1/50 second interval when the next cow in the herd would have been released, the turn of the worm that released the herd would never end. (Note, before the related fix in v3.6.25.1a, the game would have simply crashed.)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  A bug in v3.6.29.0 made it possible for a single Skunk to poison the same Worm twice, if the player's turn ended during the poisoning.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  With TestStuff enabled, "use of weapons during a rope roll" had a bug; if a weapon such as Dragon Ball (which can normally only be fired while standing or jumping) was used from a rope roll, the rope would refuse to fire during the subsequent retreat time.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  With the "BattyRope" option enabled (either explicitly or as part of TestStuff)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Ending one's turn while on the Jet Pack threw the game into an endless loop (a never-ending turn).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Guns (Shotgun, Handgun, Uzi, and Minigun) did not cut an attached rope, even with a point-blank hit to the anchoring cuff.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The camera would only follow a roping Worm if the player controlling it was holding arrow keys or pressing Space or Backspace.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  If the terrain anchoring or supporting a Ninja Rope is destroyed, it will now detach the rope. (Previously, only a standard explosion would detach a rope.) This can happen in a number of ways:\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 part of the rope becomes submerged by rising water\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}the flames from a Napalm Strike or Flame Thrower burn the land anchoring or supporting the rope\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}a Mole Bomb or Mole Squadron digs through land that anchored or supported the rope\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}a Fire Punch, Kamikaze, Blow Torch or Pneumatic Drill destroys land that anchored or supported the rope (this can only happen with BattyRope enabled)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  There was a tiny rounding error in attaching the Ninja Rope. It would often attach one pixel down, right, or down-right of where the fired rope actually hit the terrain.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  There was a tiny rounding error in centring a gun blast (from a Shotgun, Handgun, Uzi, or Minigun). The blast would often be centred one pixel down, right, or down-right of where its line-of-fire actually hit the terrain.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If a Worm tried to Bungee off a cliff, and there was a Crate resting 41 to 46 pixels below the cliff top, the bungee would fail to fire and the Worm would fall.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The CPU AI would sometimes walk through an area, jump back and walk through the same area again.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The persistent flames of a Petrol Bomb took fewer turns to decay after the arrival of Sudden Death.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  There was an extra 1.26 second delay between turns during Sudden Death with water rising disabled. This is because it took one second to raise the water by zero pixels, and a quarter of a second to linger while the camera savoured the moment.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The sprite of a Worm holding a Mole Bomb always showed the worm as standing flat, regardless of whether it may have been standing on a slope.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In a very tall map, the Mole Squadron would suddenly warp above the map after digging for no more than 36.20 seconds.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A Worm using the Pneumatic Drill while whizzing across the map (e.g., from Rope or Jet Pack, or even a jump) could hit something and make a sound effect, without actually damaging what was hit.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A Donor Card could give "-1x" of an item if the previous owner had an unlimited supply of that item. Since all teams normally have the same starting ammo, collecting this kind of donor card had no effect. Now, a donor card is no longer created if all the other teams already have an infinite supply. If an infinite supply is collected (which cannot happen anymore, barring future customisability enhancements), it will be displayed without an ammo count.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  There was no smooth transition when a poisoned Worm became healthy due to its team collecting a Health Crate.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  There was no smooth transition from the Freeze "aiming" state to the normal Standing state (e.g., when selecting Freeze then selecting Parachute while standing on land).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When landing from a Fire Punch, the Worm's sprite was not updated to reflect the land slope.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When teleporting directly on land (which can be easily done by pointing the cursor a short distance into the terrain), the Worm's sprite was not updated to reflect the land slope.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  There have been some internal fixes regarding fatal injury while releasing a herded weapon and BattyRope Skip Go. These fixes have virtually no externally noticeable effect.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In an online game, in which at least two machines connected to the game each had at least two teams of different colours, and these two sets of colours had at least one colour in common, players would incorrectly see the secrets (e.g., weapon selection and collection) of teams whose colours they did not share. (Strictly speaking this fix doesn't affect the game logic, but it is tied to the logic version for fairness.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  It has always been the case that if a worm fired the rope during a fall or jump, the rope firing would be cancelled when the worm landed, ready to be fired again right away. However, a change made in v3.6.29.0 inadvertently caused the rope firing also to be cancelled when the worm finished landing, and started standing up.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  It was possible to walk while a rope was firing, if that rope was fired while the worm was falling (from a jump, walking off a ledge, or dismounting from parachute or jet pack) and the worm subsequently landed. In v3.6.28.0 and earlier, this could result in the rope continuing to fire from the worm's hindquarters. In v3.6.29.0, it meant the rope could be fired a third time, in a different direction. It is no longer possible to walk while a rope is being fired.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The "UnFreeze" sound effect was played when a frozen worm drowned, even though the worm remained frozen.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If a missile, such as a Super Sheep with Sheep Heaven enabled, exploded extremely far from everything else (worms, oil drums, etc.), it would result in a "global explosion" due to an overflow bug.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  The team health bars were sometimes incorrectly sorted for minute differences in total team health points.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
\b\fs24 Changes\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\b0\fs12 [CS, DC]\fs20  W:A no longer registers its associations automatically upon being launched. However, the previous behaviour may be restored by checking the appropriate checkbox on the \b Advanced Options\b0  screen, or by importing \b RegisterAssociations_Automatically.reg\b0  (from the \b Tweaks\b0  folder) into the system registry.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  In-game smooth (dithered) background gradient\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  The gradient is now rendered using a new method, which should fix performance problems on some system configurations.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC, CS]\fs20  The dithering algorithm used for rendering the background for maps with more than 96 colours or non-standard height has been substantially improved.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The gradient is now drawn with a parallax effect. The effect can be disabled using the \b BackgroundGradientParallax_Disable.reg\b0  registry tweak.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The registry tweak \b SmoothBackgroundGradient_Disable.reg \b0 has been added. This tweak disables smooth gradients (forcing a coarse gradient) while still allowing the full cycle of detail levels to enable background debris, bitmap backgrounds and clouds.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Palette modification events occurring in the front end are now logged to "palette.log"; previously, they were only logged in-game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  W:A now uses some workarounds to fix palette problems in the front end. Some of these workarounds may have undesired side effects, such as flickering or delays when switching from screen to screen, even if you did not previously experience palette problems in the front end. If the side effects are undesirable and you do not experience palette problems, you can disable the workaround on the \b Advanced Options\b0  screen, or import \b FrontendPaletteFix_Off.reg\b0  (from the \b Tweaks\b0  folder) into the system registry.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  The FrontendPaletteFix registry setting, set by the FrontendPaletteFix_On/Off.reg tweaks, is a 4-bit bitfield, with each bit toggling a specific palette workaround. Thus, it's possible to selectively disable the palette workarounds by editing the registry setting directly.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  The map size prompt, which is displayed in the Join screen if the host transmits a colour PNG map larger than a certain size (the default is a width \'d7 height larger than 8 megapixels), is now also used when loading a map from disk using the Map Editor. The warning limit for the map's area can be set on the \b Advanced Options\b0  screen. As before (since v3.6.28.0), it can also be overridden by creating a value named "\b MapAreaWarnLimit\b0 " of type REG_DWORD in W:A's Options key (HKEY_CURRENT_USER\\Software\\Team17SoftwareLTD\\WormsArmageddon\\Options), which specifies the image area threshold, above which the game asks for a confirmation before loading the image. You can quickly set this value to the default value or disable the warning by importing \b MapAreaWarnLimit_Default.reg\b0  or \b MapAreaWarnLimit_Unlimited.reg\b0  (from the \b Tweaks\b0  folder) respectively.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Entering the Options screen will no longer reset the current resolution to a default value if it is not in the list of resolutions reported as available by DirectDraw.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The second asterisk (added in 3.6.28.0) has been removed from /me messages.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The host/join logs (in User\\Logs) now use a triple bullet format (like Export Log), making non-chat log entries stand out unambiguously.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When hosting a Direct IP game with a custom channel scheme (using the \b Scheme\b0  parameter) and no explicitly-specified Game ID, W:A will automatically generate and set a Game ID to prevent accidental connections with an incorrect scheme (which lead to desyncs). As usual, the correct full \b wa://\b0  URL can be obtained using the \b /url\b0  command.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  \b wa://\b0  URLs generated using the \b /url\b0  command will now specify the Game ID as the last parameter. The reason for this change is to prevent truncated URLs from seemingly functioning correctly at first, but ultimately causing a desync.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When joining a Direct IP game, the connection dialog box now says "Direct IP" instead of "Direct IP : Direct IP".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Due to general improvements in the in-game network code, a minor bug has been temporarily introduced (and will be fixed in a later version). For a client in an online game with 3 or more players, if the host stops responding (without detectably dropping the connection) during a remote client's turn, then the game will not automatically time out the connection.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Changes affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  There are no longer any built-in game time limits. These were limits that were applied in the front end but not in-game, resulting in seemingly inconsistent behaviour. Previously, if a round lasted for less than 2 seconds total turn and retreat time, it was treated as a draw. Otherwise, if it lasted for less than 5 seconds total turn and retreat time, or less than 15 seconds of total game time, the round was treated as a "win" with no winner (which was a bug).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Internal changes have been made to the "Random worm order" scheme option. This should have no discernable effect.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\b\par
\fs24 Features\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  W:A now uses Unicode for all clipboard operations when supported by the operating system.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  An \b Advanced Options\b0  screen is now accessible from the Options screen, which allows configuring new settings, and settings previously only configurable using registry scripts and direct registry editing.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The Intro can now be skipped with a single tap of the Escape key.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  It is now possible to skip the opening intro without using the \b /nointro\b0  command line option. To enable this, use the \b Skip Intro\b0  checkbox in the new Advanced Options Menu.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  All front end screens can now be exited with the Escape key.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When placing the mouse cursor at the bottom of the screen in the front end, W:A will now display a help hint.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Some combo boxes (e.g. scheme and map selection combo boxes) now drop down to taller list boxes.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  You can now jump to and cycle through combo box entries that begin with a certain character by typing the said character on the keyboard.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  List view controls (e.g. the WormNET player list) are now scrollable with the mouse wheel.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  \b Ctrl\b0 +\b Delete\b0  and \b Ctrl\b0 +\b Backspace\b0  now delete and backspace a word respectively in front end edit boxes.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When W:A is started for the first time, the in-game screen resolution now defaults to the Windows desktop resolution instead of 640\'d7480.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  When the network play screen is opened for the first time, the WormNET nickname now defaults to the Windows user name \emdash  or, if it is not available, the computer name.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When W:A is launched, the default scheme "Intermediate" is loaded. However, this is no longer done every time you enter the offline multiplayer screen and Options screen. The game will remember the last scheme loaded.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC, CS]\fs20  Clicking the "cheat" button in the Weapon Editor now flips into another screen instead of opening a modal dialog box. Currently this allows you to edit both Ammo and Delay for utilities. Clicking the "cheat" button a second time flips back to the normal weapon editor.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Provided that the computer is connected directly to the Internet, W:A will now attempt to auto-detect the external IP address by enumerating all IP addresses associated with the local hostname, and picking the first one that doesn't belong in a private or auto-configuration address range. This allows the \b /url\b0  command for hosted Direct IP games to work properly in the case that the computer's external IP has changed since the last time it connected to WormNET.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The \b /url\b0  command now also works when joining a game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The WormNET button on the Network screen now automatically connects to WormNET using the "Autologin" link. The old behaviour can be restored by replacing the file \b ServerList.htm\b0  in the Graphics\\ServerLobby subdirectory with \b OldServerList.htm\b0 .\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  A new HTML box has been added to the WormNET channel list screen. This box will be used to display up-to-date community and game-related news. 3rd-party server owners can send content to this box by placing it into <MOTD>...</MOTD> tags.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The W:A HTML parser now understands the EXTA tag. Having the same syntax as the A tag, it will create hyperlinks which, when double-clicked, will minimise the game and open the link specified by the HREF parameter in the default web browser instead of the in-game browser.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Flags have been added for \cf4 Algeria\cf0 , \cf4 Belarus\cf0 , \cf4 Bulgaria\cf0 , \cf4 Egypt\cf0 , \cf4 El Salvador\cf0 , \cf4 Guatemala\cf0 , \cf4 Jamaica\cf0 , \cf4 Kazakhstan\cf0 , \cf4 South Korea\cf0 , \cf4 Lithuania\cf0 , \cf4 Macedonia\cf0 , \cf4 Marshall Islands\cf0 , \cf4 Peru\cf0 , \cf4 Saudi Arabia\cf0 , \cf4 Taiwan\cf0  and \cf4 United Arab Emirates\cf0 .\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Four Hungarian characters have been added to W:A's font set: \cf4\lang1060\f6\'f5\'d5\'fb\'db\cf0\lang2057\f0\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  You are now allowed to use any and all characters in game names. The length limit is still 29 characters. Using the characters \cf4 "&'<>\cf0  lowers the maximum length, and these characters will show up incorrectly in older versions of W:A.\cf1  [By the time v3.6.30.0 was released, WormNET no longer translated the "&'<>\\ characters in game names in the expected way, so this feature did not work properly. See v3.7.2.0 Fixes.]\cf0\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The \cf4\'df\cf0  character is no longer automatically prefixed in front of hosted game names.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  Wrapped lines in chat history boxes are now indented. This prevents line wrapping from being abused to create fake messages.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Clipboard pasting in the front end now preserves newlines. They are shown as \cf4\f7\u8629?\cf0\f0  glyphs in the edit box, and while selecting text. When entered in WormNET / IRC, they are translated into \cf4 |\cf0  characters.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Sending notices is now supported using the \b /notice\b0  command, although W:A does not distinguish between incoming messages and notices.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  A \b /hb\b0  command has been added to the WormNET IRC lobby, which is an alias for "/msg HostingBuddy".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  Web and E-mail URLs are now automatically parsed and converted to hyperlinks in message histories (WormNET, LAN and host/join screen).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  WormNET private message formatting codes can now also be used for private messages in the host/join screen.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  New private message formatting codes have been added: \b\\u\b0  to start underlined text, \b\\U\b0  to stop.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  While the game is minimised, it will flash its taskbar button and produce a standard beep when the player receives a private message in the WormNET lobby or in the host/join screen, or when the player's nickname is mentioned in WormNET chat.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  While the game is minimised from the host screen, it will flash its taskbar button when someone joins the game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  While the game is minimised from the join screen, it will flash its taskbar button when the host lights up.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The \b /afk\b0  or \b /away\b0  command may now be used in the network Join front end screen. In the Away state, your game will automatically light up when the host lights up. This is especially useful for \cf4\b spectators\cf0\b0 . It also works for players who plan to actively play upon returning to the computer, in a casual game. In Away mode, once the game starts your turns will be automatically skipped (assuming you're not a spectator), just as if you'd entered \b /afk\b0  or \b /away\b0  in-game. The Away state will be remembered upon return from the game. In the Join screen, typing in the chat or clicking most dialog buttons will cancel the Away state.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  Pressing \b Ctrl\b0 +\b Home\b0  will enable "Home Lock", making the camera remain centred on the current worm. Pressing and releasing Home disables it.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Home (or Home Lock) will override the effect of Scroll Lock. Both can be temporarily overridden by holding down the left mouse button.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Previously, when the Escape menu was open, any team cursor (such as a Teleport or Homing Missile cursor) would be hidden from view. Now, a team cursor is rendered in quasi-transparency when other cursors are in use.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A will automatically begin ignoring in-game chat from players who send more than 5 chat lines within the same second. When this happens, a message will be displayed with unignore instructions.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  It is now possible to ignore players during the game using the \b /ignore\b0  and \b /unignore\b0  commands (in addition to the /ex and /inc commands, and using Ctrl+F1...F6). Typing /ex alone will now clear all ignores instead of ignoring all players, to be consistent with the behaviour of /ignore alone in the WormNET lobby and host/join screen.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A now saves the state of transparent labels, chat panel pinned status, home lock and the heights of pinned and unpinned chat panels between games.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The chat panel can now be shrunk (using \b Ctrl\b0 +\b Up\b0 ) to the minimum size required to display all players (as small as one line).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC, CS]\fs20  The screenshot function is now much faster. Whereas before, pressing \b Pause\b0  would cause the game to pause noticeably as the screenshot was created, it is now instantaneous. This means that the Export Video feature can now work at full frame rate or faster, even at moderately high resolutions. Note that by default, Export Video goes no faster than the normal frame rate; to get it to go as fast as possible, adjust the playback speed by holding \b 0\b0  while pressing \b 9\b0 .\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The Export Video dialog box no longer has an upper limit on resolution.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  It is now possible to automate Export Video by specifying export parameters on the command line, after the /getvideo switch. The order is as follows: \b /getvideo\b0  \i ReplayFile\i0 .WAgame \i framerate-divider\i0  \i start-time\i0  \i end-time\i0  \i resolution-width\i0  \i resolution-height\i0  \i basename\i0 . The syntax for the values is the same as in the Export Video option dialog box. At least the frame rate divider must be specified; other parameters will be set to their default values if not specified. This feature can be used to extract a single frame as an image, by specifying the same start and end time.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Pressing \b Space\b0  during the playback of a recorded game will now skip to the beginning of the next turn.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Weapon Panel\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  In v3.6.28.0 it became possible to view the weapon panel during other players' turns, but the panel was still being automatically closed at the beginning and end of local turns, even though it could be reopened right away. The panel is no longer ever automatically closed; only a player's direct actions will close it.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Previously, it was not possible to view the weapon panel during other players' turns if there were multiple players on the same computer with different team colours. Now, a menu of team colours is displayed at the bottom of the panel in these cases, allowing the inventory of any local team to be viewed by clicking the team's colour swatch.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  It is now possible to view the weapon panel during playback of a recorded game. A menu of team colours is displayed at the bottom of the panel, allowing any team's inventory to be viewed by clicking the team's colour swatch.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When the weapon panel is redrawn, the cursor position is now remembered even if it was on an empty square of the grid, or on a weapon that disappeared during the redraw. Previously, the cursor was reset to the upper-left corner of the panel in these circumstances.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Previously, Select Worm was hidden from teams with only 1 worm. Now, it is displayed in disabled form. (This is important if you have a stockpiled Select Worm that can persist to the next round.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  During manual placement at the beginning of a game, it is now possible to "reselect" the Teleport. This has no practical value and is just for consistency and fun.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Selecting a weapon from the weapon panel will now automatically close the chat panel.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  A new "Saniti\ul z\ulnone e Replay" feature has been added. This creates a copy of a replay with all \cf4\b private chat\cf0\b0  messages \cf4\b removed\cf0\b0 . To use this feature, right click on the WAgame file in Explorer and click "Saniti\ul z\ulnone e Replay". The file "\b replay.wagame\b0 " will be sanitised to "\b replay \{sanitized\}.wagame\b0 ".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  It is now possible to view the contents of crates and fuses of random mines during playback of games played with v3.6.29.0+. Previously, these were displayed as question marks. This feature has not been made fully convenient yet; currently you must fast-forward almost to the end of the replay and then [R]estart it to see the contents of crates and fuses of random mines.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The Teleport fudging algorithm (which tweaks the position of the cursor if it is not precisely located in a spot allowing space for a Worm) is now much better at reading the user's intentions. If any fudging is needed, it will now be biased towards placing the Worm directly on land.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The resolutions in the Options Menu combo box are now sorted by total number of pixels. Resolutions that are identical in total number of pixels are sorted by height.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Host/Join screens and the in-game chat box, entering the command \b /time\b0  will display the current local time.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When using "Extract Scheme" on a recorded game file having an old logic version but including settings in its scheme that are interpreted by newer versions to represent customised Mines / Oil Drums and/or Jet Pack fuel, the extracted scheme will now have these settings reset to their default values, so that a game played on the latest version using this scheme will have the same settings as the actual recorded game did.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In v3.6.19.12, the Map Editor's Generate button was removed, and replaced with a Reseed button. The Generate button has now been brought back (inserted above the Reseed button), and generates exactly the same maps as it did before being removed.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Test versions\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  BattyRope, 150% Speed, and TestStuff have all been added to the latest game logic version, so that older versions will not need to be emulated to enable these options.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Girder Radius Assist has been added to TestStuff.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Note that TestStuff has been incremented to "version 8". However, emulation of earlier versions of TestStuff is now allowed.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Some new test versions have been added:\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\b RacingStuff:\b0  This can be toggled with any one of the following commands: \b /rs\b0 , \b /race\b0 , \b /racing\b0 , /\b racestuff\b0 , or \b /racingstuff\b0 . This enables Phased Worms, in which worms pass through each other without resistance, and enables worm selection without ending hot seat time. This option is especially useful for Bungee Races.\par
\b{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}BoomRacing:\b0  This can be toggled with any one of the following commands: \b /boom\b0 , \b /boomrace\b0 , or \b /boomracing\b0 . This enables Phased Teams, and enables worm selection without ending hot seat time. This option is especially useful for Boom Races and Assault Courses.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Phased Teams creates a condition in which enemy teams cannot influence each other in any way \emdash  with some exceptions:\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li1260 The landscape is shared, so terrain creation (girders, arrows) and destruction (explosions, Fire Punch, Kamikaze, Blow Torch, Pneumatic Drill, Mole Bomb, Mole Squadron, Napalm Strike, Flame Thrower) influence all teams. Worms standing on terrain may fall if that terrain is destroyed or pierced by an arrow; the creation of terrain puts an obstacle in the path of enemy teams, and its destruction removes an obstacle.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Rising water drowns all teams, regardless of who or what caused it to rise.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Destroying an Oil Drum will remove it as an obstacle, meaning Worms that were standing on it will fall.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}If a Mine placed on startup is triggered by proximity, it will only directly damage allies of the team that triggered it. However, its disappearance will mean that it can no longer serve as an obstacle for enemy teams.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Anything that creates flames (Napalm Strike, Petrol Bomb, Oil Drum explosion) may erase pre-existing flames if the maximum number of flamelets is reached. The flames erased may belong to an enemy team.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Enemy Worms will visually hide the terrain covered by their sprites. (This is also a shortcoming of Phased Worms.)\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}These shortcomings may be addressed in a future Beta Update.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC, CS]\fs20  Export Log changes\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  The WAgame file format version is now logged, right after the game logic version.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The W:A version used to export the log is now logged as well.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The turn time totals and associated team and player names (at the end of the log) are now formatted for improved readability.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Export Log will no longer fall into an endless loop when emulating the BattyRope Jet Pack bug. Note that there are other endless loop bugs that Export Log does not handle yet.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The "Damage dealt" log entries now include an accounting of kills.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The exported log will now indicate which player was the host.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180 Readme entries for versions in which CyberShadow and Deadcode collaborated (v3.6.28.0 and onward) have been annotated in small print to show which developer(s) implemented each fix and feature.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 [DC] means it was implemented by Deadcode (David Ellsworth).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS] means it was implemented by CyberShadow (Vladimir Panteleev).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC] means it was primarily implemented by CyberShadow, with adjustments by Deadcode.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC] at the root of a tree means that most of the subentries were implemented by CyberShadow, and the rest by Deadcode.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Note that the [CS] and [DC] tags indicate coding credit only, and do not cover planning discussions and documentation edits.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
\cf4\b v3.6.31.0 Beta Update (2010.11.16)\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  In emulation, /version messages, and Export Log output, W:A v3.6.30.0 incorrectly called the test versions "v3.6.30.0[BattyRope8]" and "v3.6.30.0[TestStuff8]" "v3.6.30.0[BattyRope7]" and "v3.6.30.0[TestStuff7]", respectively. It incorrectly called "v3.6.30.0[BoomRacing]" simply "v3.6.30.0", whereas it incorrectly called "v3.6.30.0" itself an empty string, "".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Some features specific to internal testing (alpha) builds were accidentally left in v3.6.30.0.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.29.0: The game would sometimes crash during the worm death explosion animation, if the Russian language was selected.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.30.0: If, after joining a network game as a client, the user pressed the Escape key in the join lobby but clicked "Cancel", then subsequent clicks of the "Exit" button would display the Quit confirmation dialog box, even though the default behavior of the "Exit" button in that screen is to instantly quit. Alternatively, if, instead of clicking the "Exit" button, the game was started, and sometime during that game round the user quit, then W:A would show a Quit confirmation dialog box after switching back to the front end.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.30.0: On some systems, there was no sound in the front end. Starting with v3.6.30.0, W:A checks if the sound parameters requested by W:A are supported by the sound card's DirectSound driver. On some systems, the DirectSound driver incorrectly reported the sample rate used by W:A as out of range of its hardware secondary sound buffer sample rate specifications. W:A now does not check if the desired sample rate is within these specifications.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.5 Beta 1: If front end audio initialisation failed, minimising and restoring the game in the front end would result in various graphical artefacts, such as a mostly-black screen with white text and missing mouse cursor. This problem appeared for all users affected by the above problem.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Despite the v3.6.30.0 fix preventing a momentary switch to 640\'d7480 when launching replay playback, the display mode was still being set twice, redundantly (to the configured resolution both times). W:A now sets the display mode only once, which results in a faster launch on some or most systems. This also fixes the bug in which, on some systems, attempting to export videos from replays at certain resolutions failed with a front end video initialisation error message.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.29.0: The Russian file type description for .WAgame files was not being correctly registered.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The Hungarian characters introduced in v3.6.30.0 could not be typed in the front end.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.30.0: The WormNET news window was being cleared when returning from a game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  LAN games hosted by v3.6.30.0 were only joinable via Direct IP due to Game ID checks and the fact that all versions before and including v3.6.30.0 did not send a correct Game ID for LAN games. Both problems have been fixed \emdash  v3.6.30.0 LAN hosts are now joinable by v3.6.31.0+ clients, and v3.6.31.0 LAN hosts are now joinable by older (v3.6.30.0 and earlier) clients.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.28.0: On some systems, the smooth background gradient was not being rendered properly on very tall maps.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Map complexity and randomness\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.30.0: Loading a particular .BIT or .LEV map caused mouse-click terrain generation to iterate through the same sequence of random maps every time that same map was loaded (either by the local user, by another user who downloaded that map, or by the host of an online game which the user joined). This behaviour is now changed \emdash  the sequence of generated maps will be different each time the respective W:A screen is opened, regardless of the initial map.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Worms Armageddon will no longer store the RNG seed used for map generation and other tasks in the registry. Instead, a new seed is generated on each start, using a cryptographically random buffer. This removes any possibility of persistent effects on a W:A installation's RNG.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  When trying to connect to a v3.6.31.0+ game with a v3.6.31.0+ client using an incorrect Game ID, W:A will now show an appropriate error message instead of "Max Players".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The Italian translation for the "Prod" weapon has been changed from "Pungolo" (in the front end) and "Bastone" (in-game) to "Spintarella".\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\b\par
\fs24 Features\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  A slider has been added to the map editor, which allows controlling the range of complexity in randomly generated maps. This slider affects map generation outside the map editor as well, but not for Quick CPU and Deathmatch games (which will continue to be generated at maximum complexity). By default, the slider is set to the maximum complexity level, similar to the behaviour in versions v3.6.20.1 to v3.6.29.0.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  A new registry script, \b ResetRegistryOptions.reg\b0 , has been added. Importing this script will reset all Worms Armageddon options from the Windows registry. The \b Reset\b0  button in Advanced Options (added in v3.6.30.0) also does this, but also clears the options stored in win.ini.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The "\i team\i0  (\i player\i0 ) forced out by \i reason\i0 " message that is printed in red in the in-game chat, and also printed in Export Log, is now more descriptive in cases where the cause may be a HostingBuddy bug or message injection.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
\cf4\b v3.6.31.2b Alpha Update (2012.09.12)\cf9\b0  - first Steam release\cf4\b\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Removed stub .WAgame context menu entry for "Convert to Beta" option, accidentally left in v3.6.30.0 and v3.6.31.0.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Intrinsic scheme files were being created with filenames in an incorrect encoding.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.19.17: When Extract Scheme was used on a mission/training replay, it would crash or behave abnormally. The correct behavior is to refuse to extract the scheme, because the configurability of missions is currently not representable in the scheme file format.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  W:A now fails gracefully instead of crashing when attempting to load a BMP file in User\\Flags containing an invalid header (e.g. zero-filled).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.29.0: When the tweak \b StereoFactor\b0  was set to a value less than or equal to \b DisplayXSize\b0 *2, W:A would crash when starting a game. For example, with 1920\'d71200 as the configured game resolution, setting "Stereo effects" in Advanced Options to anything from 0% to 5% would result in a crash when an attempt was made to start a game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.5 Beta 1: The custom resolution selection drop-down was being disabled when the team limit (32 teams) was reached.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In an offline game with "Weapons Don't End Turn" enabled, a supply of multiple Longbows, and Instant Replays enabled, it was possible to crash the game by triggering an instant replay while Longbow arrows were in the air.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Fixes affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  If the Bungee was triggered on the same frame (at the same instant) as damage to other worm(s) began to be displayed, the Bungee would instantly be cancelled and the Worm using it would fall and lose its turn. (This bug could only happen if BattyRope was not enabled.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.30.0: If a rope that was not perfectly vertical was allowed to settle into a perfectly vertical resting state, and then a Girder or Longbow Arrow was created inside the rope, the worm dangling from the rope would "accelerate" due to gravity while actually staying still at the end of the rope; when released, the worm would then fall downward at an artificially high initial velocity.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When an Indian Nuclear Test (2 poison points) was used right before the onset of a Sudden Death Nuke (5 poison points), the loss of health due to poison was applied twice (once after the Indian Nuclear Test and again after the Sudden Death Nuke). Each time only the Indian Nuclear Test's 2 poison points were applied, ignoring the Sudden Death Nuke's 5 poison points on that turn and subsequent turns. The fixed behaviour is now to add the poison points (2+5=7), applying the cumulative poison only after the Sudden Death Nuke and not between the two nukes.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If a worm standing on land placed a Girder next to a moving or jittering object (e.g. a worm), such that there was adequate clearance the moment the mouse button was clicked, but blockage on the following frame, the Girder would be placed anyway, intersecting with the object that should have blocked it. An analogous thing happened for Teleport, except that the worm would enact the Teleport animation and sound without actually teleporting.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In v3.6.30.0, a fix to a glitch accidentally had the effect of increasing the average depth of the Pneumatic Drill from 158 to 185 pixels, and significantly changing the probability distribution of its depth. The average depth and its statistical characteristics have now been restored to legacy behaviour.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In a Crate Shower, it was possible for both Super Sheep and Aqua Sheep crates to fall, regardless of whether the Aqua Sheep was enabled or not.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
\b\fs24 Changes\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\b0\fs12 [CS]\fs20  W:A will now use the larger font for the in-game chat and network panel on resolutions of 720 pixels in height or taller, as opposed to the old value of 768.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[T17:CB]\fs20  W:A now uses 32-bit colour graphics modes both in the front end and in-game. Internally it still uses 8-bit palettised graphics, with a software renderer converting to 32-bit colour in real time. This fixes all remaining OS-related palette glitches.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
\cf4\b v3.7.0.0 Update (2012.12.20)\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC,CS]\fs20  Compatibility and interoperability\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Windows 8 compatibility has been improved.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When W:A is run under Windows 8 for the first time, it will offer to configure Windows compatibility flags which should improve compatibility and performance under Windows 8.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Problem introduced in v3.6.30.0: WA.exe triggered a false positive in some virus detection programs.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Support was added in v3.6.28.0 for opening land*.dat map files from OnlineWorms and WWP Aqua in W:A's Map Editor. However, three land*.dat maps (land07.dat, land21.dat, and land27.dat) from the Korean small version of OnlineWorms could not be opened.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in features introduced starting at v3.6.19.15: With the command-line parameters \b /getmap\b0 , \b /getscheme\b0 , and \b /getvideo\b0 , the use of forward-slashes instead of backslashes in the file's path name was not supported.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.23.0: After connecting to a non-WormNET IRC server that attempted ident authentication, W:A would fail to properly join channels.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC,CS]\fs20  Default files, folders, settings, and persistence of settings\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  W:A will now create empty user content subdirectories on start-up if they do not exist.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS, DC]\fs20  W:A will now create a default team file if one doesn't exist.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The \b /register\b0  command-line parameter will now report errors, and also save W:A's install path.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When registering its associations, W:A did not override the current "Open With" user choice.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When a host enabled one of the "test versions" (BattyRope, RacingStuff, etc.), this state was meant to persist both through multiple rounds and new matches, as if the enabled test version were part of the scheme. However, it did not persist through new matches.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.30.0: After returning from a Mission or Training, the default scheme would be incorrectly set in Offline Multiplayer.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Intrinsic maps were not remembered in Offline Multiplayer mode; every time a Multiplayer screen was entered (including the end of a game round), a selected intrinsic map would be overwritten with a randomly generated map.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When a replay file using an intrinsic map was launched, the current map (stored in current.thm) was deleted. If this was done while another instance of W:A was open, this would cause the map thumbnail in that instance to become empty (or, in versions before 3.6.29.0, garbled).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When an online game was joined, and the host loaded a .BIT or .LEV map (without necessarily starting the game), on the client's side, it would result in a state in which part of the representation of the current map was not updated. In this state, if the client-side user entered the Offline Multiplayer screen, the last map loaded by the host in the online game would be shown \emdash  but if the user then right-clicked it to open the Map Editor, the incorrect map would be opened.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  After a round of Training, in-game options such as volume and detail level were not being saved.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC,CS]\fs20  User interface\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC,CS]\fs20  Compatibility tweaks in the Advanced Options screen that were obsoleted by v3.6.31.2b have been removed.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\fs12 [CS]\fs20  The "Slow Frontend Workaround" setting is now a checkbox, which selects between the previous "Off" and "Alternative" settings. The previous "On" setting has the same effect as as "Off".\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  When playing on very wide maps (at or close to the map width limit), moving an aiming cursor (e.g. Teleport) to the right edge at high speed (especially when using Shift and/or the middle mouse button) could result in the cursor wrapping around to the left edge.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Map Editor, when moving the mouse out of the map and back in while holding Alt (for fine tuning) the entire time, the coordinate at which the brush cursor re-entered the map did not match the coordinate at which the mouse cursor actually re-entered.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When moving the mouse over the Map Editor's drop-down list of files, the help text for controls underneath the list box would be shown.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Despite the wraparound fixes in v3.6.28.0, when playing on very wide maps (at or close to the map width limit), a worm flying off the right edge of the map at very high speed could cause the camera to wrap around to the left edge. A speed sufficient for this was only possible if "no maximum speed" was enabled (e.g. by TestStuff).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Options screen, if a team was created, edited, or deleted, the Language combo box would have the entire list of languages repeated at the bottom of the list (in an A-B-C-A-B-C manner); this would continue to happen each time (A-B-C-A-B-C-A-B-C, etc.), until exiting the Options screen.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.30.0: In an offline game, selecting a weapon using the mouse (in the weapon panel) would cause the next attempt to open the chat panel (to make replay annotations) unsuccessful \emdash  the chat would open a little bit and then immediately close itself.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  In-game mouse movement input handling has been improved. Previously, W:A would incorrectly accumulate earlier mouse movement input messages received within the same frame, and in specific circumstances, W:A could get stuck at a black screen when starting a game or restoring after minimising during a game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When the primary DirectDraw surface was lost, it was not being restored correctly. This needlessly slowed down restoring W:A after minimising by one frame.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Rendering of background gradients (both in-game and in the main menu) has been optimised.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Front end buttons were not highlighted instantly upon mouse-over, but rather, only when the mouse was moved from one point on the button to another point on the button.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.19.7: In the Network Host screen, when the Start button was enabled and the host's mouse was over it, and then a remote player turned their light bulb off (disabling the Start button), if the host subsequently moved the mouse, the Start button would be redrawn as if it were enabled, but it would not highlight upon mouseover and would not respond to being clicked. It would go back to normal the next time it was enabled by having all players light up.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Under Wine, pressing ESC anywhere in the front end would instantly propagate to all windows, usually resulting in an instant exit.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC,CS]\fs20  Cosmetic video/audio issues\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC,CS]\fs20  Bugs introduced in v3.6.31.2b\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\fs12 [CS]\fs20  The brush cursors in the Map Editor were incorrectly rendered.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The phone icon, meant to be displayed only when the chat panel is hidden and a remote player has just said something in the chat, would (under certain conditions) be shown fleetingly when closing the chat panel (with PageUp) or decreasing its height (with Ctrl+Up).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The water level slider in the Map Editor rendered its blue fill rectangle incorrectly.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When running the game at a high resolution such as 2560x1600, on some systems, minimisation in-game could sometimes result in a constant flicker when the game was restored.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Steam version of W:A, there was a bug in which custom soundbanks would not be heard in-game, except for the soundbank of the first team in the list of teams. For all other teams, the default soundbank of the local player would be heard.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Front end checkboxes would sometimes be drawn with a weird-looking solid background, if the checkbox was ticked when the front end screen containing it was entered. This was random every time the screen containing the checkbox was entered, and more likely on some machines than others (but very unlikely on most machines).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Front end group boxes were improperly restored after minimising; their text captions were being redrawn in bright white instead of grey.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The button to open a front end list box would be temporarily erased upon opening certain list boxes for the first time after entering a front end screen.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When exiting from the Offline Multiplayer or Network screen into the Main Menu, there would be a single-frame flash of incorrect palette. This had been a latent bug since v3.5 Beta 1, but in v3.6.31.2b became a reliable bug that happened every time.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.19.7: When entering a Next Round screen a second time during a Multiplayer/Online match (i.e. on the second round or beyond) the auxiliary palette of the map thumbnail would be lost. For .BIT and .LEV maps this resulted in a loss of anti-aliasing; for .PNG and intrinsic maps it resulted in a peppering of black pixels over the thumbnail.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In certain conditions a GDI-style 3D frame could be seen around the W:A logo in the Main Menu. Usually it was only seen upon quitting \emdash  for a moment, the border would be visible against an otherwise completely black background when the screen was cleared. However, on some systems the border would be visible at the same time as the logo, clashing with its intended look.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.19.7: In the front end, the help text for a default-disabled button would always be shown immediately upon entering a screen. For example, "You're all set let's go!" would be flashed (or shown) upon entering the Multiplayer or Host screens.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Activated utilities displayed in the lower-right corner of the screen (in-game) were rendered with black pixels in all four corners. The corners are now transparent.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.23.0: During playback of a game in which Invincibility ("god mode") was enabled, it was impossible to hide the display of crate contents and precise mine fuses, even at the minimum info detail level.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When W:A started the Intro after 60 seconds of inactivity in the front end ("attract mode"), the menu loop ambient sound continued to play.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Elements of the background debris in the front end would only become visible when they could be drawn entirely on the screen, which caused them to materialise suddenly on the left and top sides of the screen.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC,CS]\fs20  Text and translations\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  The Spanish translation has been corrected, improved, and extended by OutofOrder.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The French translation has been corrected, improved, and extended by LeTotalKiller.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The Russian translation has been corrected, improved, and extended by CyberShadow and StepS.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Weapon Editor's "cheat" mode, the utilities now have proper help text.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The description text for the "Grenade skills grade 3" stage of Basic Training gave incorrect information in its Dutch, German, Portuguese, and Spanish translations.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Some English and Portuguese text has been corrected.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The Dutch, French, Portuguese, Russian, Spanish, and Swedish translations had some Mission briefings that didn't fit on-screen. Furthermore, briefings that reached the bottom of the text box had their bottom line of text cropped below the baseline.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The Dutch, French, German, Italian, Portuguese, Spanish, and Swedish translations of the "Spectral Recovery" mission briefing had extra text in them (compared to the English text) which may have made it easier to complete the mission successfully in fewer attempts.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Displayed and outputted text\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  After clicking the "cheat" button in the Weapon Editor to flip into cheat/utility editing mode, and then clicking it again to flip back, the help text for the top five weapons on the left column were incorrect.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.31.0: In the Map Editor, the help text for the terrain texture button vanished when the button was clicked.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When changing the current language in the Options screen, the name of a currently selected intrinsic scheme (e.g. "[ Intermediate ]") was not updated.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The \b /url\b0  command in the front end network screens did not include custom ports in its output.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.30.0: When an unrecognised command with a parameter was entered in a host/join/LAN screen, the error message was incorrect, e.g., the command "/win gold medal" would result in the error message "Unrecognized command /wingold medal".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.30.0: When copying a string from the chat history in the front end, the Unicode copy of the clipboard string was not being null-terminated. All Windows versions seem to deal with this gracefully, but in Wine, this would sometimes result in some stray characters being inserted at the end.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS,DC]\fs20  Error messages, prompts, and confirmation\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Team file save failures are no longer silently ignored.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A will now display warnings on start-up when files in the current directory are not writable, or if W:A was run "As Administrator".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Upon starting a Mission / Training exercise, if W:A encountered an out-of-range setting while parsing the .WAM file, it showed an error message dialog box \emdash  but went ahead and started a game anyway, with an incompletely initialised mission scheme.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Advanced Options screen, the Escape key would instantly exit the screen without saving changes. Now, it prompts the user whether to exit without saving changes.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  In the Advanced Options screen, W:A will now notify the user when changing options that only take effect on the next start of the game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The Delete button in the Map Editor did not ask the user for confirmation.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  After loading a PNG with more than 112 colours in the Map Editor, exiting it and clicking OK in the dialog box that prompts the user to dither to 112 colours, there was no immediate visual response to the OK button being clicked. Now, the mouse cursor changes to the Busy state while the dithering is being done.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Graphics and audio error messages have been greatly improved, and now communicate detailed localised error messages, API function names, error codes and their descriptions.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Should the graphics system fail to initialise, W:A will now offer to reset the graphics settings to the default safe values.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  When attempting to repair a replay containing a map error that the "Repair" feature is not currently designed to fix, W:A would display a blank message box instead of an error message.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS,DC]\fs20  Text would appear cropped if W:A attempted to display a message box or confirmation box in the front end containing more text than would fit. Message boxes are now sized to fit the entire text.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Text in some of the Host screens' buttons would appear cropped or inappropriately wrapped in some languages. These buttons are now resized if necessary to fit the text into one line.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Numerical ranges\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.28.0: In the Map Editor, if Placement Holes were adjusted above 255 (up to a maximum of 300), the number would be truncated (it would have 256 subtracted from it), e.g., a count of 300 would become 44. The maximum is now truly 300, but to use a Placement Hole count higher than 255, all players must be using v3.7.0.0 or later.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.28.0: In the Scheme Options editor, the health crate energy was shown incorrectly upon entering the editor if the value was above 127.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The maximum air retreat time supported by the game logic is 255 seconds, but the Scheme Options editor only allowed it to be adjusted up to a maximum of 127 seconds. Any value higher than 127 (adjusted using an external scheme editor) was shown incorrectly. (Note that the game logic really does only support a maximum of 127 seconds for land retreat time, as opposed to air retreat time.)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC,CS]\fs20  Crashes and memory corruption\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  It was possible in theory for W:A to enter an infinite restart loop, where each iteration would start a new process instance and immediately exit. This could happen if W:A reliably crashed before it processed its command-line parameters.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When an error was encountered creating the output file for \b /getmap\b0  or \b /getscheme\b0 , or the output folder for \b /getvideo\b0 , W:A would crash instead of displaying a proper error message.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.30.0: If a host selected a map file larger than 5120 bytes, and then switched to a map file 5120 bytes or smaller while the earlier map was in the process of being sent, the host would get an "Out of Memory" error leading to subsequent problems.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Certain out-of-range numeric values, or too many events, in a .WAM (mission/training) file could cause W:A to crash when loading the corresponding Mission/Training round.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A team file (WG.WGT) edited using an external editor to have a team name of 17 characters (with no terminating null) could make W:A crash if the corresponding team was teamed in locally in an online game, and then clicked to team it back out. Other bugs may have also resulted from having the team name and/or other strings in the team file of maximum length with no terminating null. These strings are now forced to have a terminating null if they don't already (e.g., the team name is now forcibly limited to a maximum of 16 characters).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Wine would sometimes crash when audio streams were played in the front end. These streams (in Data\\Streams on the CD-ROM or under the main W:A folder in the Steam version) include the intro title music, the Mission/Training win/lose sounds, and the music played at the end of a multiplayer match. The front end now uses the same API as is used for in-game ambient music (also in Data\\Streams).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Minimising during the Intro resulted in a crash upon restoring.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  If W:A attempted to set an in-game resolution wider than 2048 or higher than 1536 and failed, W:A would get stuck at a black screen directly after the loading pie. The lock-up was due to W:A continuously failing to move the mouse cursor position to the "center" of the expected resolution, which was outside the screen area of the actual fallback resolution (1024\'d7768).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  A potential security vulnerability has been fixed.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Fixes affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  It was possible for a Double Time crate to fall in a scheme with infinite turn time. This was inconsistent with other aspects of the game logic; for example, crates never fall containing contents that are already at infinite ammo in the scheme.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A bug in the Spanish translation of "N Shots Remaining" caused an exclamation mark to be inserted in front of the number ("Quedan !N Disparos") and caused the message to be queued up, instead of flushing the game comment / morse code text queue as it is supposed to (like weapon selection messages also do). Under contrived conditions, it was possible for this to lead to a desynchronisation, if there was a mixture of players, one or more of whom had Spanish selected as their language, and one or more with a different language selected. Besides being fixed, the bug is also now emulated in online games and replays thereof.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  With BattyRope enabled, if a worm was still on the Bungee upon winning the game, its bungee would be detached (to do the victory dance); as a result it would fall down and possibly lose the game instead of winning.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  With BattyRope not enabled, if a worm with a perfectly vertical rope attached was touching the ground, and pending damage on another worm was ready to be displayed, the rope would be detached. (This usually happened with a Ninja Rope that had just been fired straight up.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If a player disconnected while their team(s) were frozen, they would stay frozen for the rest of the game (or until drowned). Teams are now automatically unfrozen upon surrendering.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bugs regarding Blow Torch / Teleport and explosions / impacts\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  A worm using the Teleport (at the stage in which the wavy-light teleportation animation is showing) would have its teleport interrupted, if and when an explosion happened anywhere on the map (out of range of damaging the teleporting worm); if the worm was in the air at the time, it would also lose control. (Note, in WWP, this bug also happens for a worm using the Blow Torch.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A worm using the Blow Torch, when hit by an explosion, would not be pushed by the impact. (Note, in WWP this was fixed, at the cost of introducing the above Blow Torch bug.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A worm using the Blow Torch, or using the Teleport as described above, when hit by a Dragon Ball, Longbow arrow, or flamelet, would not be pushed by the impact. (For this to happen with a Dragon Ball or Longbow arrow, "Weapons Don't End Turn" would have had to be enabled. With a flamelet, it would be rather subtle, as the first flamelet to hit would cancel the Blow Torch or Teleport, and subsequent flamelets would act normally.)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Bugs enabled by very high or unlimited maximum speed\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  It was possible, despite the wraparound fixes in v3.6.28.0, for a worm to fly off the right edge of the map at very high speed and wrap around to the left edge, if the worm was still in control at the moment it flew off the edge. A speed sufficient for this was only possible if "no maximum speed" was enabled (e.g. by TestStuff).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If the maximum projectile speed was set to a value >=200 pixels per frame, or unlimited (like TestStuff3), it was possible for an object to fall so fast that it skipped past the water and disappeared without making a Splash sound effect.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If the above-described glitch happened to a Worm, it would disappear without losing its energy, causing the game to prematurely end the round with an "Avoid Crash" when the game tried to give the current turn to that worm. (Note: The description of this particular "Avoid Crash" has now been edited to be more universally correct and informative.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If the maximum projectile speed was set to a value >663 pixels per frame, or unlimited (like TestStuff3), it was possible for a Worm to fall fast enough that its Fall Damage would be improperly calculated, taking a meaningless value in the range 0 to 1820.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Health bar bugs\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  If a team surrendered before collecting a health crate, and the addition of the health to the team's total energy made it at least 25% higher than the best total energy of any team so far in the current round, then the health bar would overflow beyond its maximum length and would be drawn in a glitchy way. In extreme cases, the health bar could even stretch beyond the right edge of the screen.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If a team was damaged and then collected a health crate while the damage was still pending (i.e. before the damage was visually subtracted), and the addition of the health crate to the team's total energy (with the pending damage already subtracted) made it at least 25% higher than the best total energy of any team so far in the current round, then the health bar would overflow beyond its maximum length and would be drawn in a glitchy way. (This could at most make the health bar slightly less than double what its maximum width is supposed to be.)\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
\b\fs24 Changes\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\b0\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Resolutions are now denoted in all places in the front end as <width>\'d7<height> instead of <width>x<height>.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The message sent from the host in the Network Host/Join and Next Round screens, informing the players that the game cannot start due to unsupported features (map, scheme, and/or number of worms) by a subset of players who joined, has been streamlined.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
\b\fs24 Features\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\b0\fs12 [CS,DC]\fs20  Advanced Options screen\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  An option has been added to load WormKit modules on startup.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 By convention, WormKit modules are DLL files whose name begins with "wk".\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The command-line parameters \b /wk\b0  and \b /nowk\b0  also control this behaviour, and take precedence over the Advanced Options setting.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The command-line parameter \b /wkargs\b0  causes W:A to ignore following command-line parameters. This can be used by WormKit module authors to allow passing parameters to WormKit modules.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS,DC]\fs20  An option has been added to use 8-bit colour DirectDraw rendering. As in v3.6.31.2b, rendering is performed in software. As a result, the 8-bit colour mode is more similar in performance to v3.6.31.2b than it is to earlier versions (which used 8-bit colour with hardware rendering).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  An option has been added to use Direct3D rendering. Direct3D may bypass compatibility and performance issues present with DirectDraw, and enable interoperability with software such as the Steam overlay.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 It is possible to select using either Direct3D 7 and 9 APIs. The respective DirectX runtime needs to be installed.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Selecting \b Direct3D 9 (shader palette)\b0  causes the palette transformation to be performed on the GPU (using a pixel shader). This lowers CPU usage, but requires Pixel Shader 2.0 support on the GPU.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [CS]\fs20  An option has been added to control waiting for vertical sync. Lowers latency when disabled, but may cause screen tearing.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS,DC]\fs20  An option has been added to enable additional synchronisation between screen refresh and vertical sync ("Assisted vertical sync"). Enabling the option should lower latency.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  An option has been added to enable use of hardware mouse cursors. Currently this option only affects the front end. When enabled it eliminates all perceptible lag between moving the mouse and seeing the cursor move on screen, except for the brush cursor in the Map Editor which is still software-rendered. Enabling hardware cursors results in a much more dramatic difference in this version than it would have before v3.6.31.2b, as software rendering has resulted in higher lag in the front end.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  An option has been added to configure the compatibility flags for Worms Armageddon in the Windows registry. The configured flags improve performance and resolve GUI issues under Windows 8. (Credit for discovering the compatibility flags goes to StepS)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  An option has been added to use a new CommunityServerList.htm file instead of ServerList.htm, which, upon connecting to WormNET, redirects to a third-party server list linking to community WormNET servers.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 The game will automatically offer to toggle the option in case of a WormNET connection error.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Drop-down list box (and combo box) behaviour\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  When clicking outside of a list box, the mouse click used to be discarded; it now behaves like a normal click on an outside control.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When right-clicking outside of a list box, the mouse click used to be completely ignored (it wouldn't even close the list box); it now closes the list box and behaves like a normal right-click on an outside control.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Mousing over controls outside of an open list box now highlights them and shows their help text, the same as if the list box were not open.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The button that opens and closes a list box now behaves more gracefully.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  If a list box is currently open, the ESC key will now close it instead of exiting the current dialog box or screen. (Since v3.6.30.0, this behaviour applied to the Multiplayer screen's Scheme combo box and the Map Editor's Map combo box, but no others; now it applies to all combo boxes and drop-down list boxes.)\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Scrollbar buttons now repeat-scroll only while the mouse is inside the button (while the mouse button is held down).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  It is now possible to start an "online" offline game from the Network Host screen without using the light bulb button, if there are no remote players.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS,DC]\fs20  Translatable strings have been moved into external text files.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 The language files are installed to the DATA\\User\\Languages\\\i n.n.n.n\i0  directory, where \i n.n.n.n\i0  is the Worms Armageddon version.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}User-created language files can be placed in the User\\Languages\\\i n.n.n.n\i0  directory. This is the recommended location to place new or modified language files, as files in this location will take priority over those under DATA\\User\\Languages, and are not under risk of being overwritten by a reinstall.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The command-line parameter \b /langdir\b0  can be used to specify one or more directory paths which override the locations where W:A will look for language files. The directories are searched in reverse order (the last specified location will be the first one searched).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The language file format and syntax is as follows:\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 Each file must use UTF-8 character encoding, and start with the corresponding Byte Order Mark. (The Byte Order Mark is usually invisible in text editors with Unicode support.)\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The first line is reserved to indicate the language name (in the corresponding language).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The rest of the file is a list of strings. A string is defined by its identifier (composed from uppercase English letters, digits and underscores), followed by one or more string literals (which are joined together when the file is loaded).\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}A string literal is a sequence of characters surrounded by double-quotes, and may contain the following escape sequences:\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li1260\b\\"\b0  - literal "\par
\b{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}\\\\\b0  - literal \\\par
\b{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}\\n\b0  - line break\par
\b{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}\\m\b0  - 1.5\'d7 height line break (where applicable)\par
\b{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}\\1\b0  through \b\\9\b0  - placeholder for the first through ninth parameter\par
\b{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}\\,\b0  - substring separator (for randomly-selected substring container strings)\par
\b{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}\\\{<\b0\i XX\b\i0 ,\b0  and \b\\\{>=\b0\i XX\b\i0 ,\b0  - begin conditional block. All characters until \b\\\}\b0  will be included or omitted, depending on whether the current game version is respectively smaller-than, or greater-than-or-equal the indicated version number (in hexadecimal).\par
\b{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}\\\}\b0  - end conditional block\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900 A comment begins with the \b #\b0  character and continues until the end of the line. Comments are ignored by the game.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540 The set of visible characters is currently limited to Worms Armageddon's custom character table ( \cf4\ul http://worms2d.info/WA_character_table\cf0\ulnone  ). This limitation may be removed in the future.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Translation improvements and new translations can be submitted for inclusion via the Team17 forum \cf1\b (see section 7.0)\cf0\b0 .\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Changes affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  When a Double Time crate is collected during retreat, the remaining retreat time is now doubled.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When a Double Time crate is collected by an animal, the animal's remaining fuse time is now doubled.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fs28\par
\cf4\b v3.7.2.1 Update (2013.03.11)\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\b\fs24 Fixes\b0\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [CS]\fs20  Disabled the unfinished crash log uploader, which was accidentally enabled in v3.7.0.0.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A will now display a warning when attempting to select a Direct3D 9 renderer on systems where it could lead to excessive or continuous screen flicker \cf5\b (see section 4.0)\cf0\b0 .\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A will now gracefully handle an integer division by zero crash in VMware's accellerated graphics implementation, and treat it as a graphics initialisation failure.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A will now offer to switch to alternative graphics settings if the default ones result in a graphics initialisation failure.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A will now suggest trying the Direct3D 9 (shader) graphics API to Windows 8 users when launched for the first time.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  W:A will now suggest enabling a Direct3D-based graphics API when Shift+Tab is pressed while using a DirectDraw-based API in the Steam edition. (The Steam overlay does not support DirectDraw.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  The W:A update installer will now detect and offer to remove WormKitDS (dsound.dll), as its functionality was added in W:A in 3.7.0.0 in the form of the "Load WormKit modules" option on the Advanced Options screen. The built-in option is preferred above WormKitDS for improved stability and interoperability.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.30.0: After returning from a Deathmatch, the default scheme would be incorrectly set in Offline Multiplayer; it would claim to be Intermediate, but was set to 1 round to win instead of 2 rounds.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the v3.7.0.0 French translation, extra strings were added to six game comments, with the conditional wrapper "\\\{>=EE," "\\\}". This triggered the error message "Unknown character in conditional" due a bug in v3.7.0.0.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the v3.7.0.0 French translation, two strings were added to GAME_CRATEDROP_COMMENTS and two to GAME_SUDDEN_DEATH_COMMENTS, but each pair of comments was incorrectly entered, and would have been concatenated into a single comment if displayed.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Minor spelling corrections have been applied to the English text.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[CS]\fs20  Minor grammar corrections have been applied to the Russian translation.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The French translation has been extended by LeTotalKiller, including all new strings added since v3.7.2.0, and a couple of minor corrections.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The instant replay countdown timer, displayed in the upper-left corner of the screen during an instant replay in a mock-digital-watch font, incorrectly displayed the hundredths of a second as repeatedly counting down from 60 instead of from 100.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Combo box bugs introduced in v3.7.0.0\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Clicking the mouse button on the single-pixel-thick border of a combo box's list box closed the list box.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Releasing the mouse button on the single-pixel-thick border of a combo box's list box caused a stack overflow crash.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In the Host/Join screen, the down-arrow button on the scheme and intrinsic level combo boxes was accidentally and improperly widened by 4 pixels.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Latent combo box bug introduced in v3.6.19.7: If clicking on an item that was already highlighted caused a dialog box to pop up, it was possible for a crash to happen upon dismissing the dialog box.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Bug made possible in v3.6.20.2: It was possible, but rare, for the "Nonstandard Weapon Power levels" warning dialog box to cause a crash upon being dismissed, if it had been triggered by selecting a scheme from the combo box in the Host screen.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug made possible in v3.6.30.0: It was possible for the "Large map warning" dialog box to cause a crash upon being dismissed, if dismissing it caused a map to be successfully loaded.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  If W:A was installed from the Czech CD-ROM before being Updated, the Team Editor would not work properly due to failing to load the gravestone bitmaps with Czech filenames. It would either crash upon entering the Team Editor, or show blank fields for everything except the team and worm names.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.29.0: The \b /dir\b0  command line parameter will no longer be overridden by the executable's directory, even if this results in W:A not being able to start properly.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.7.0.0: In the crash report file "errorlog.txt" there was a line ", version 3.7.0.0" which started with a comma.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.7.0.0: Most of the non-chat lines in User\\Logs\\*.log started with "???" instead of "\bullet\bullet\bullet ".\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.7.0.0: A potential crash / security vulnerability in custom language files has been fixed.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Additional sanity checking is now done on data received while connecting to a host.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.28.0 and v3.6.29.0: In the Join screens, the \b /version\b0  command would show the incorrect version for a host using a version in the range 3.5 Beta 3pre10 - v3.6.27.3q. (Note: Since hosts using these versions do not report their version to the client, a client can only deduce a version range depending on what protocols and formats the host uses.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.30.0: Using the characters \cf4 "&'<>\\\cf0  in game names on WormNET now works properly, and no longer decreases the maximum length of a game name. This is accomplished by translating the characters \cf4 "&'<>\\\cf0  to the non-printing characters 0x10, 0x11, 0x12, 0x13, 0x14, and 0x15 respectively.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.7.0.0: When starting WA.exe with \b /langdir\b0  parameter(s), combined with either "Auto-register associations" enabled or the /register parameter, the command line registered for \b wa:// \b0 URLs did not include the /langdir parameter(s).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.31.2b: Tall maps satisfying a certain inequality regarding their width and height could cause a crash upon starting a game. The formula in C-like pseudocode is: tilewidth=((height / 30) rounded down to nearest multiple of 8); if ((tilewidth - (width % tilewidth)) is sufficiently large) then crash upon starting a game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.30.0: If the user pressed the Escape key in the host/join round-finished lobby but clicked "Cancel" in response to the Quit confirmation dialog box, then subsequent clicks of the "Exit" button would display the confirmation dialog box, even though the default behavior of the "Exit" button in that screen is to instantly quit.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.24.2: With "Offline rope knocking" enabled, it was possible for a Deathmatch to be started with rope knocking enabled (which isn't supposed to happen). This would happen if the user started a Quick CPU game, then after finishing it, started a Deathmatch without first exiting the Single Player menu or closing W:A.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When the "Create new team" button was used from the Training screen, the background particles behind the Team Editor moved twice as fast as they should.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.7.0.0: Using the \b /ignore\b0  command in the WormNET lobby (IRC) would cause an immediate crash.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.5 Beta 1: When minimising in-game, if any keys were held down at the moment of minimisation, then upon restoring, the game would continue to think the keys were held down, even if on the physical keyboard they weren't. Conversely, if any keys that weren't held down at the moment of minimisation were held down upon restoring, the game wouldn't necessarily detect that they were held down.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.7.0.0: When using a Direct3D 9 renderer, restoring after minimising in-game in single-step mode (during playback) would result in a black screen unresponsive to keyboard input (subsequently resuming normal operation required clicking a mouse button to restore the display, then again clicking a mouse button to restore keyboard focus).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.7.0.0: When using a Direct3D 9 renderer, restoring after minimising in the front end would not give focus to keyboard input until the mouse was clicked.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.19.17: Pressing \b Space\b0  to skip an instant replay did not work while in single-step mode.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.28.0: If the current map was a cavern with a width narrower than the current resolution, when the chat panel was visible, an area of matching height on the bottom of the screen would have graphical artefacts in its left and right sides, because the black letterbox area mistakenly excluded those regions.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.5 Beta 1: After minimising an offline game using \b Shift+Escape\b0 , animated effects that don't affect game logic (such as smoke and flames from explosions, smoke rising from Petrol, Homing Missile and Super Sheep trails, etc.) continued to be animated; as a result, by the time the game was restored, usually all of the effects would have already been finished and fizzled out, and in many situations would then be recreated all at once, putting the animations into an artificial-looking simultaneous phase until the passage of time allowed them to stabilise again into comfortable chaos. (The same thing has always happened when pressing \b Escape\b0  to pause, but as changing this would significantly affect the look and feel of the game unless done right, it has been left as-is for now.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.5 Beta 1: When playing on a cavern map with a height smaller than the current resolution (i.e., a resolution high enough to result in letterboxing on the top and bottom), rising water caused a fluctuating inconsistency in the on-screen positioning of sprites and land. This effect was particularly obvious when using fast-forward, and when using "Playback at" with "Start Paused" checked.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.29.0: Export Log did not log the ending of the last turn (along with its turn time, retreat time, and damage dealt), if it was ended by locally quitting the game.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.30.0: When playing back a replay file that was recorded with a W:A version that records the passage of time between turns, if the file ended abruptly without an "exit" message at a point between turns, the end-of-game fade-out would be unnecessarily delayed until the beginning of the next turn.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.30.0: In-game bitmaps (including the health bars, text boxes, wind bar, and weapon panel) having a width and/or height of an odd number of pixels were drawn one pixel left and/or above where they should be, respectively. In most cases this is an arbitrary distinction, but not in the case of the turn, retreat, and round timers, which were being drawn one pixel up and to the left of where they should be within the timer box.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.20.1: In an offline replay created by the first version of W:A to save replays (v3.5 Beta 3pre7a), the message "Detected pre-2003.12.07 GMT game file (no checksums)" would be printed every time a checksum was found to be missing (this message was supposed to be printed only once).\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  A fix in v3.6.26.4 prevented Mission Attempts counters from going over 127 and wrapping into the negative numbers, however, if playing missions with a version earlier than v3.6.26.4 already caused the counter to exceed 127, the latest version of W:A would still treat the number of Attempts as negative.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  When the Map Editor was in Preview mode, changing the water level did not immediately update the previewed positions of Placement Holes. Toggling the top (cavern) border did not update the preview either, even though it can change the positions of objects.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  In versions prior to v3.6.28.0, the water level of a map was limited to 50%, and setting it anywhere from 51% to 100% in the Map Editor would be equivalent to setting it to 50%. This limit was unwittingly removed in v3.6.28.0. One bug resulted from the presence of this limit in earlier versions, and another bug resulted from the removal of this limit:\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  The water level was never correctly previewed in the Map Editor. The 50% limit was not taken into account, and the on-screen water level preview had been calibrated as if maximum water level (which happened to be 50% of the map height) was only reached at 100%, i.e. as if the water level increased linearly from 0% to 100%; as a result the water level was displayed as if it were half of what it really was.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.28.0: When a version earlier than v3.6.28.0 was emulated, and the map was set to a water level greater than 50%, the game would desynchronise immediately. Now, when hosting a game, if the water level is greater than 50% and there are client(s) present using a version earlier than v3.6.28.0, the game will not be allowed to start.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.6.28.0: When emulating a version earlier than v3.6.28.0, it was possible for a desynchronisation to happen under the following circumstances:\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  A Strike weapon is used, and by the time the plane disappears, all of the objects released by the strike are gone, and nothing else is in motion. There are at least two known ways this can happen:\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\tx810 The scheme is set to zero retreat time, and a Strike weapon, set to "zero power" in the scheme, is used. Since it releases zero missiles, no trickery is needed to get them to disappear quickly. The next weapon use will desync.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The scheme is set to less than 3 seconds retreat time; an Air Strike with 1 star of power is aimed at three towers of Frozen Worms piled at the top of the map near the left edge, and all four missiles hit the towers near their tops. By the time the plane disappears, the bouncing motion of the frozen worms has damped down to zero. The next weapon use will desync.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  A missile with "zero power" is created in a position where it already intersects with something that would make the missile explode upon impact, after the worm responsible for firing the weapon is already idle. There is no known way this could happen.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li180\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Fixes affecting game logic\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  It was possible to place a Girder partially underwater if the water level was higher than the bottom of the map. Subsequent water rising would only erase the part of the girder that was initially above water, leaving an invisible obstacle in the water.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The game would crash if a CPU Worm, while enumerating possible places to which to walk, reached its maximum search depth at a point in its path where it would fall and retain control. \b (See Footnote 2.)\b0\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug introduced in v3.5 Beta 2: CPU Worms would always shoot Strike weapons to the right, and never to the left.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.26.4: The absence of this bug in v3.0 was not emulated.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\tx810\fs12 [DC]\fs20  The glitch in which targetable weapons (such as Homing Missile, Air Strike, and Teleport) could be fired without being targeted has been modified. It now only works in the form of pre-targeting, which must be done on the same turn as which it's used.\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  The v3.6.31.0 Fix, \i "The game would sometimes crash during the worm death explosion animation, if the Russian language was selected"\i0 , changed what comments in GAME_LAND_DEATH_COMMENTS would be randomly displayed for players who had the Russian language selected, but did not implement emulation for what comments were displayed in earlier versions. Emulation for this is now implemented.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li540\fs12 [DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.28.0: On a map of width greater than about 32304, shooting a rope off the right edge could result in the endpoint of the rope wrapping around to the left side, resulting in its line segment being incorrectly drawn. (The same thing could happen on a map of height greater than about 32304, shooting a rope down into the ocean.) (Strictly speaking this fix doesn't affect the game logic, but it is tied to the logic version so that all players will see the same thing.)\par
\fs12{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}[DC]\fs20  Bug in a feature introduced in v3.6.28.0: When playing on a map of height 32568 or greater, objects falling into the water would sink forever without drowning, preventing the turn from ending. Now, the visible height of the ocean will be decreased in such situations to allow objects to drown normally.\par
\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-180\li900\fs12 [DC]\fs20  When this bug occurred, it was always accompanied by another one: The current worm was not tracked by the camera. This bug is now fixed without being tied to the logic version (i.e., it won't be emulated when the other bug is emulated).\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
